\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Can you tell me where and when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 I was born - on July the twenty-third, 1893, 
in Dumfries, do you want where - Friars Vennel. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 How long did you stay in that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh well - I can't remember leaving it, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You were quite small then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Well, I'd be about three years old - I think, and that's when - went to S
ummerville, came here to Summerville, and I was in Summerville for - nine years. So I was about eleven or twelve, when I left Summerville, and came to live in Glasgow Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Why did you change that time, did your father change his job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 My fathe
r changed his job, he'd been with Mr Davidson for - nine year. I don't know why he changed his job, but it wasn't anything - you know - he didn't fall out with him because - Mr Davidson - always used - to send for my father, to see to his orchids, he was 
a great orchid man, Mr Davidson was, and - he always sent for my father - to attend to his orchids.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Even after he had finished working for him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes, after he - after he finished working. - Oh yes, were quite friendly. However he went to work with - a Mr Service who had a nursery - in the Colebury Hill. Oh well that's Marshaltown then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 So it was the same sort of job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes, the - the glass houses and all that, work like that. He was - he was the - very efficient in glass houses, you know, anything growing - under glass, and outside it too of course, everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was he always a gardener?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes. My -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 That's what he trained as when he was young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 My - I've heard my mother say - he - he had his apprenticeship - with - C
harlie Scott that's Scott of the mills, that used to have the tweed mills, as I - have heard. He was a millionaire - in these days of course - lots of millionaires now but he; was a millionaire then. And - there was ten gardeners, that was - it's a girls 
s
chool now, Woodbank, Mansion House, that's - on - Edinburgh Road. Woodbank Mansion House, that was - Mr - Scott, Charlie Scott, that's who my father - he had ten gardeners. It was a big gardener - big garden and - I have - lots of his - you know, when he 
w
as looking for a job, the - references - from - and from there and from Summerville too, and - how efficient he was, so - and I had a great aunt, my - my father's aunt, she was cook there. She was cook there at the time my father was an apprentice gardene
r. Of course - he was there before my mother - before - my - my mother married him, he - that's where he served his apprenticeship, until he came - a journeyman and that's where he came to - Summerville. From there. So -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 What sort of job did your moth
er do before she was married, did they meet in the way of business?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well, my mother - worked in - a - her brother-in-law's hairdressing - salon, that was - on Buccleugh Street, before Hillingbran or all these were - there's another German in it. His 
name was Henry Brown. I don't know how many people alive today who will remember him, but I remember him - faintly, he's married to my - mother's sister, you see, and she - stood in the shop, and she used to go out and do the ladies hair - curl them with 
t
he tongs, cut them and put the flowers in when they were going to balls as they called them then, the big dances. My mother done all that. And she used to say to me she never had a bit of powder on my face. I said, well - if you'd put me in that shop you'
d have been }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 bankrupt}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
. She says, I never put anything on my face. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Would there be many people went to the hairdressers shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well there were more - more the gentry then, it was more - ladies - and the - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 aristocrats}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  you know that didn't have a
 maid, they had - it was all - I heard my mother say it was all long hair and she used to do the singeing, and the tong curling. And - putting it up - round their heads and the - the earphones and all things like that. That's before she married my father 
but she didn't go back after. No. But I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 She would have her family to look after?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was your father a gardener all his days then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 All his days. Yes, all his days. He was a horticulturalist.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
I had two brothers, and two sisters, that was - and myself. That made five. Five of a family. My brother was - older than me, he also was born on the Vennel. My two sisters were born in - at Summerville. One of them died - when she was eight
een, she was - poisoned - with - dope, at the Arrol Johnson when they were doing aeroplane wings, she was just eighteen. Tetrachlorophine poisoning. She never had a doctor. In fact she hadn't picked a doctor, that was the time when you had to pick doctors
, she was four years younger than me. And she was eighteen. She was only a week ill. The - dope - destroyed her liver. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was it an accident then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well, no. It was - and by - about that time I'd - I'd - had I met my husband, that was my husba
nd like, eventually, and I told him about it. He says, oh in the - aeroplane shops - down - in the RAF they give them plenty of milk to drink. Yes. Well she she never had milk - to drink. They used to let them out - about - for half an hour in the morning
, half an hour in the afternoon for fresh air. And she always used to tell my mother that - lots of the girls were sick. But she never was sick, you see, she took it into her - she never got rid of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 It must have built up in her body then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Well
 - there was a person came into the shop where I worked, and she was the head of these girls, and she - started to talk to me, I didn't know who she was. And - she was very sad about - Iona, she said. Was - was she your sister? I said, oh yes. And I told 
h
er, I says, you know - she never had milk to drink. I said, and I had a friend who told me they always had - about a pint or two pints of milk - a day, to kill the poison. And as my mother never knew it was - would be fatal there, she loved her work. She 
w
as a great worker she was. Even in the house, and - oh, she said, after that they got milk to drink before the inquest came on, they - and in the court - they said - that they had the milk to drink. Well they never - my mother couldn't fight them. It was 
m
e - she told. Well they - they had - the finish they had milk to drink, well they did have milk to drink, but they didn't have milk to drink when she was there. Accidental death. And because her father was alive my mother got nothing. And - just a wee bit
 - the wee bit insurance that they insured them against fatal accidents. And - and of course her father was alive. But at the time my mother wasn't - bothering much about things like that, she was too - it was the first break in the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You don't think of the money at a time like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No. No. But - she was full of life. She was full of life, she never - she just - some morning she felt sleepy, and my - my mother took her to the doctor's, Doctor Hunter. And - he says, it's a - he said she had 
the jaundice, lost - it did give her the jaundice because it was - the liver, and - he said, she'll soon be all right now. Well - she never was all right, she - she just died. And - when they took her to hospital - and - my father and mother were - by her
 
bedside, and the sister put her head through the - curtain and she said, poor girl, she's been poisoned. You see, and that much - she knew. Well my mother told Doctor Hunter. Oh nothing of the kind, nothing of the kind, that's for the chemist to find out.
 
Well, she says, I say she was poisoned. Well about three months after that - my mother - was ironing, she heard a voice calling up the stair, are you in Mrs Cardol? He says, I've come to tell you that Iona was poisoned. She said, I told you that three mon
ths ago, when she died she was poisoned. Oh well, eh says, we didn't know it - it's a new thing altogether, that the dope - had done it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 But they knew down in the South?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes, in the RAF.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 That there was a danger.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 They should have passed it on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
But they didn't have milk to drink. That was the first case here, and of course they came from the Home Office and everywhere and - I assure you - your - daughter has died has saved the death of - soldiers in the battlefield. She
 said, aye, but that won't bring her back. There was the war on you see when she died. However that passed, well she was - she was just eighteen at the time. Just }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 beginning}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  her life. Mm hm. That'll be - many years would be - would that be now - she would h
ave been - four years younger than me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 That would be 1897?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Uh huh. 189 - oh three I am.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Can you tell me about your house here at Summerville, can you tell me what size of house it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Well, it was a whitewashed stone building. It had
 - a kitchen downstairs, stone floor. A fireplace with an oven - beside where you lit the fire underneath here. Lit the fire - underneath the oven when you wanted to bake.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 But you had the ordinary fire at this end?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 The ordinary sway come down th
e fire with a big girdle on it or the broth - pot. The walls - in side - were boulders, you know, just chipped - sandstone, not - not - not smooth like this.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 It wasn't plastered inside?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 No, it was stone. Stone floor. And - that was where - we h
ad no water laid on. But we'd plenty of water in the lock, to do the - other work you know that needed - cleaning water, and - the fresh water was brought down from near the big house, and it - stood on the scrubbed white table, in buckets. Uh huh. And -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Who had to go and fetch the water?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh my father. And - we had barrels outside for rainwater. Which my father always washed in, rainwater.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 They say it's best for your skin.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Uh huh. And then we had the loch, plenty of water there. Of cou
rse that was harder water. Spring water. But drinking water - oh yes, but not for drinking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 But for the likes of doing the washing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes, yes. Then - but - up in the big house in their wash house they had water. They had taps you see. But the 
gardeners - the gardener didn't have it. No. And - we had - upstairs, we'd a big bedroom, and another living room. And downstairs the other side was a big - great big place but that was - they used to keep the implements in - and the potatoes and things i
n
 that. That wasn't a living room. But that was attached to our house. So - we had a window - two windows in that room one into the garden, and we had - father had walled - fruit, which grew up the wall. And the cherries used to come in the window, we used
 to - pick the cherries. Little window, and - and when the cherries were ripe - put your hand out, they had wall - pears - greengages, I don't know what - all fruit, grew on a wall - on the wall, not on the - be trees but grew - up the wall.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You youngsters would like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 And, we had plenty of everything. Plenty of vegetables. Never went short.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was that sort of taken as part of your father's wages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes, he would - we were - his wages were only nineteen shilling a week. Free house. And your - vegetables, and fruit. Flowers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 It was just your other food that your mother would have to buy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 And tomatoes, my father was a great tomato grower.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 He was keen on green houses of course?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes. Yes. Melons, grapes. Of course -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
You would be getting fruit that the other youngsters in Dumfries would never see?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well - it was cheaper then. Fruit was cheaper, but of course - so were wages weren't they. I've heard my mother say - she used to come down from Dumfries, and she
 used to go to Tom Gibson that used to have a grocer in the Vennel, well - he used to send the orders - to her. What she had got. She used to say to me, if ever you grow up, she says, and you get married, don't deal in one shop. She says, just go - and bu
y
 what you want with your money. For she says after you've bought all you want you've nothing left. She says - you've nothing - you've nothing left. She says - many a time - she told me, many a time - when - perhaps - before she had - carrying one of us - 
s
he says, I daren't look at a shop window, in case I saw something that I wanted and I couldn't get it. But she says - I never owed anybody anything. But she says when you put your money on that one shop, she says, you see something - see something and so 
you buy it. Well you've got to learn to do without. So - now that was Summerville.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did all you children sleep in the one bedroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well - my brother wasn't, there was - there's four of us. One of them had a cradle. There - there - there was a bed 
in that living room. And my mother - my mother and father and the cradle for the youngest one. Well in the other big bedroom it had two beds in it. Well us girls were all in the one bed, and my brother - the one brother in a - a cot or something, a small 
b
ed, in that room. And it was paraffin lamps. For the - the lighting. And my mother perhaps - she would forget sometimes - and have to come down into the town. Well there were no lights - from - Leicester Street school was the last lamp. There wasn't a lig
ht }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 firm}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
 Glasgow Street school - until my mother got into her house, up in Summerville. The avenue was as black as pitch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You were really in the country then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes. There was no lights in Glasgow Street here. The school was the last one. Not a ligh
t, it was all - in fact it was all green fields - and - one - one house. One house. That was the - Hazelbook. Was the house, and it was a miss Dudgen, one of the Dudgen's - that had the - you know, out there - the big house - out the - on the other road. 
The Dudgen's. They were the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you use torches in these days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Beg pardon? No, no. Just the moonlight. I can't remember - a torch in these days. Can't remember having a torch. No wonder - I was always afraid of ghosts. Ghosts were my pet aversi
on. I was always seeing ghosts. But - up - sometime my mother used to ask me be - when I came out of school, I went to - Glasgow Street school, perhaps to bring the Standard, or - pepper or - little things like that that you forget. Well - Joe Beattie, hi
s
 father had the shop, it's gone now, what's there now, where are we, oh the gardens down in Glasgow Street, he had a little grocers shop there. You went down steps to it. Perhaps I'd go there to get Standard, and when I come out of school - maybe pepper, 
I
'm not just taking things and - maybe marmalade you know, run out of marmalade, and I'd meet some of my friends from the school and of course we'd all sit down in the footpath and tell stories. And all at once somebody would say it was getting dark, about
 
four o'clock, Oh. I got home. Got up the road. Dark, it was dark by then before I got up, and my mother - had come down - to meet me, thinking I was - bit longer than I should have been, and she used to wear these white aprons, you know, the bib and - tie
d up behind. And I could see this bit of white apron just - coming out, I could see that. I thought to myself, oh it's the Sort of Spring Hill jake, my mother's spook.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 So you'd hurry home the next day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 I hurried home the next time, and - my brot
her never was - afraid but I was, I was afraid of that - dark avenue. However I loved Summerville. I did, I loved Summerville.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 And you would have lots of room to play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes, plenty, the fields and all, fields, and the - Mr Hastings the butcher
, he had a butchers shop down - foot of Glasgow Street, he used to - hire these fields that, belonged to the estate you see - for his cattle. Well I - there was one black - I think you would call it a stirk, like a young bullock. Well - it used to leave t
he herd - and come over to us children. And it stayed with us all day - we used to ride on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 its back}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 . It - and it - we called him Jenny, by the way. And - and well one - I think it was my sister, my mother went out for a walk after she'd had my sister like s
he had - a system you know they had the swaddling clothes then, the long - carrying it, and it left the herd and it came over to see what she had in her arms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 They say they're curious beasts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 I can see - I can see that black - animal now, coming
 over - as soon as we opened the - see it was walled all round, soon as we opened the - the garden - the door in the garden wall, it came to us. And it stayed with us. That was funny wasn't it. And you know as the years went on - I used to say to my mothe
r
, where did Jenny go? She - it would go for - butcher meat I suppose, you see these are the ones that they - eat - eat it. My mother said, oh I think they put him away in another field. And I never saw anymore about it, but it - it disappeared. But that -
 that black - animal was - was one of our playmates.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Just like a dog would it be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes. It was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you have dogs and cats around the house?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
We had cats, I had cats, my mother always had a cat. And - a bit tom cat. Doctored like, he - 
he used to bring rabbits galore home. And one day he came home - in half - with his tail in two halves, you know - this round and the other part like that, but of string or something, and bone, and he'd been in a - one of these gin traps. That had been pu
t
 down for the rabbits and he got his tail in it. So - there was some painters working up there, I think they were putting up green houses - and they told my mother just to - bring a board, and give the cat some milk, and they took the axe and chopped it o
ff. And we were all crying you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 I suppose it was the only answer really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
It just - it just looked round to see what the noise was, and it went with its tail in a bandage.. And it was stumpy after that. Well he was a - he would go for the - l
ittle birds in the nests. But - my father - in this walled - fruit, my - there was a bird had its nest there, and - they'd fallen out. Well my father got a little cage with the wide spars on it, they couldn't get out, and - put it up and - the mother and 
f
ather used to come and feed them, at the window. Because the nest had gone too, it had been a storm I think. And - the cat got up and ate them. Clawed them through the - and my father says, I'll murder it. He took it and he threw it out that window. Into 
t
he garden, he just threw it out. And we, oh Tom's dead, Tom's dead, we called him Tom, and we went down - the stair and here he was sitting washing his face at the front door. Nine lives. So - oh you couldn't stop him from hunting you know. He was a prope
r poacher. And one day - he brought one - prize bantam, a lovely bantam, and then he went away and got the other. It must have been somebody's prize bantams.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 He would be popular?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh - popular. And - the butcher that owned the field - said he seen
 him - the sheep and the lambs used to lie about in the field, and he'd take one race at them and chase them all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 always}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  - there was a rabbit hole, and he says he's watched him sit and wait 'til the rabbit came out and he just nabbed him. And he used to go 
in the loch and bring out the water hens. Swim after them. Right hunter. However - now -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did anybody else ever live in the house with you and your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No. Just my father and mother and - ah, just the family together, and a happy family we were, my mother was always there and there was always plenty of - good baking and - things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 She baked a lot did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
She baked and then of course, this - great aunt of my father's - who was - great aunt of mine I should say, my father's aunt, she 
was a cook, well she was the - retired then, she used to come up and do - baking, and big tables used to groan with all different scones, tarts and - baking things, and herring all done in oatmeal. Crisp on a plate, I can see them now. The herrings.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Your great aunt would have the knack of laying things out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes. And - well - well we always - in these days really we were better off than we are now. And food was - more wholesome. We used to go up to Loch - field, that's where the garage is now, th
at was a farm, and get the milk. My brother and I. We had these big cans, you know, the - hooked - handles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You had to go and collect your own milk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes. There'd be a - quart of - new milk, and - a canful of skimmed milk, and another of buttermilk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was the buttermilk for using on your porridge?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 No, for scones. Scones. My mother always made them with - with buttermilk.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did she make bread as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No, my mother never made bread. But scones - she made cake, and - I don't know, she didn't make shortbread, she made - her own cake, fruit cakes, Christmas time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 And she would be a jam maker I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh plenty of jam. I - we used to get pear jam. Jam. The pears were cut in lumps. And - there was - I don't how they were do
ne but they come out in a syrup, and the apples was done the same, and ginger in them. Currants, gooseberries - everything you could think of. We never - I never - never went hungry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did she pickle things like onions and beetroot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Beetroot, yes,
 but - well my father was very fond of pickles. So maybe she did do that
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did she ever make any medicines herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 A lot of the countrywomen used to make their own medicines.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Ah, with the - herbs, no, she never - she never 
made medicines but - when we had the toothache - which we - used - used - well you have the toothache, and you know there were no dentists then, the doctor pulled them out. Ah - I can feel it now, and - she used to get a piece of brown paper. Like blottin
g
 - brown paper, you know, the way - an old blue sugar bag used to be, the old fashioned sugar - that was soft and like blotting paper, not the shiny brown paper, and she used to - put pepper on it, cut a square. Put pepper on it, and vinegar, rub it in. A
n
d that was clapped on your cheek, and there were a cloth put round your jaw, that was a counter irritant and you used to get to sleep. It used to - it so - it was a - you felt that burning and it didn't burn your skin, but you felt - your skin was all rig
h
t the next day. It was the heat in the pepper and the vinegar, and that was - her cures for toothache. And - I used to love the smell of the pepper and the vinegar. But we all - I say we always got to sleep, with the pepper and vinegar brown paper on our 
face. Yes. And it - you felt it - you felt it burning, but - it didn't - mark your skin. Never never touched - spoiled your skin. Mm hm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did your mother make your clothes herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Or did you have shop bought ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Well - they w
ere bought in a shop - and I - think - that I used to do the altering, lovely sewers, by hand, because you had little petticoats you know, we had with the little bodices on them. And then your frocks - I think they were bought. But she used to - have to p
atch and mend. Different things like. I don't know as - we were always kept tidy and clean, starched - starched pinafores - when - when we'd been away you know, flying. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 How about shoes, did you wear boots?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Well - I had - the world's - first
 pair of feet I think for fitting. Still have. High instep. Well we used to wear clogs, in the weekdays. Clogs. They were the fine thing for your feet. The wooden soles and the - carkers as we used to call them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Are they studs in the heels?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 No, 
they were round - round heel part was steel and a - a piece like that - on the wood. We used to go to the shop - and - have them done with the cloggers, a set of - carkers }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 as}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  we called them, caukers. And why - I'll tell you something about that, while we w
ere in that shop we used to hunt for - pieces of leather, square piece of leather, and we would ask the - the man to - round it, put string through it with a knot, what you called a sucker. And we used to lick it you know. Put it on a stone - in the groun
d
, a cobble, and it stuck and you lift - could lift the stone out. And then you'd take it off and lick it again, I said, well we're still here. Goodness knows what we would think about - even the leather, licking the leather, it was pure leather. Well that
'
s - we used to go with this thing on a string and my mother used to say - if the police see you doing that - what you'll get. This was when we come to Glasgow street here. But we had - boots, and clogs. And our Sunday boots - were special, your clothes we
re all special for Sunday, you never wore your Sunday clothes in the weekday.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Even if your Sunday dress was getting old, you didn't wear it out on the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well - well perhaps we did, yes, I think we did. But - my mother used to have my boots m
ade at - Bryans. That's Bryan solicitor's father, he had a shop in the Vennel and they were glace kid, and they were buttoned - up here. We had to have the button hook, that the - do them. Well these were - Sunday night I used to - on Sunday morning - we 
u
sed to go to church, my brother and I, from Summerville, Greyfriers church, go to my granny's for the - dinner. She was on Brewery Street. And she tidied us up if we needed tidying up and we went to Sunday school in the afternoon. Came back for out tea at
 my grandmother's. She used to belong to Marshaltown West Church and we went there. At night, and then she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 brought}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  us home, to Summerville.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 This was just you and your brother was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Brother and me, yes, she brought us home to Summerville.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Your mother and father would look after your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes, my mother never - got much to the church you know, she had always too much to do for she'd to do outside work - round the - you know, the parks and things like that. Not weeding, keeping - brushing them down to the house. There was always plenty -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 This was part of your father's contract was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well no, she just - no, no, she just kept it clean, and - our clothes were - taken off and were put out - our house frock on. Th
ey were all brushed, folded - and my mother had - what they called a kist, you know, oak - chest, the old oak chest, they called it a kist. And I would have to carry them - she opened the kist lid, and they were laid reverently in that kist until next Sun
day. And your boots were put - all polished and put away. They were soft soft kid. Well by the next week I think your feet must have grown. Talk about }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 
in growing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  toenails, some - my feet must have grown from one Sunday to another, because when I put them on they hurt me at the toes. However - life went on.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you hand on shoes to your younger sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Beg pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you hand on clothes and shoes to your younger sisters?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You know, I don't know. I don't think mine were fit to hand - to 
hand on. The way I kicked them. But we had - then in the summertime came - we wanted to go barefoot. Because we had summers that you could go barefoot. And we - of course it was to get into the water that we wanted barefoot, but lots of children went bare
f
oot. You weren't poor because you were barefoot. And we used to say, can I go barefoot? No. You can go slipshod. That's take your stockings off and put your shoes on. Slipshod. And as soon as we got - away from the house, off came the slipshod. We were ba
refoot. Then we'd go into the ninth down here. Wading. And somebody'd step on a broken bottle. Piece of glass. Then when you got home you got a good hiding for - going barefoot. Going in the water. It was - you got the tawse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 At home too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 On your
 bottom. You got the tawse on your bottom for - doing what you shouldn't have done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Who smacked you at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
My mother. My mother. My mother, not my father. Father never laid a finger on us. My mother I think was both - father and mother as far 
as that was concerned. Oh yes, but - mother - your mother was always there, and your mother always - at night time before we went to bed we were all washed - your hair - mother insisted they were put in papers for curl - they'd curl the hair, mine was pla
i
ted, two plaits. And - we were washed, and your things were all - clean and - you had - bread and milk. Bread and - could make bread and milk these days, not now, not bread and milk now. And sugar. Bread and milk and sugar. I used to love that. That was o
ur supper. And - in the morning - we had our breakfast, we had our porridge. And - we always had either egg, sausage, black pudding, something like that, bacon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You had a good breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes. And - if my mother had - hadn't any bacon, we used to 
get what they called French toast. She used to cut the - bread, and beat up a egg, and soak it in the egg, fry it and we always had it spread with sugar, it wasn't a savoury one. You know I loved that. And that - heated you up, in the morning. We never we
nt to school without something in our stomachs. Hot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did your father have his breakfast with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh no. He got his - he got his earlier. He - we had to be at the school nine o'clock well my father was out all hours. The gardens you see and he'd 
perhaps come in for his breakfast. But they were breakfasts, now I couldn't take that breakfast now. Even if I could afford it, I couldn't take a breakfast like that now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 But you were young then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 We were young. And - you had a good dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You got home from school for your dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Got home from the school for your dinner, and - it - that same Hastings the butcher - I'm telling you about, on the Tuesday and the Thursday they used to do their own killing you see, there were no market ki
lling then. They done their own killing, and - the liver - we used to - well, children that went for liver high and low, two penn'orth of liver. And you got lov - he wouldn't give it to you if it was pipey, he'd say, no - no liver this morning, it was pip
e
y. And - you get pipes and everything in it now. Well it was lovely or liver, or sheeps liver. No - the sheeps liver, you know a pluck - a sheeps liver's all on it, a great big liver, well there was that, and the heart, and - meat hanging to it, you got t
hat whole pluck for sevenpence ha'penny. A whole sheeps liver.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 That's what you make haggis with isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes. Well - yes. But the - the - the - lights - lights go into haggis but - my mother - used to give them - the cat, the cat got the lights.
 They were boiled for it, but there was the liver, and my mother used to slice that liver - and stew it with onions. And what a grand dinner }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 that was}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you always get meat for your dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes, we always had meat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes
. Or fish. Meat or fish. Now - that - my mother - with - with a - with a - a - a pluck - she made what they called hashey, soup. It was like hare soup. The liver was boiled - the heart was boiled, it was all grated, and - she made a stock, with the bits o
f meat that were - hanging round it, and - all that and vegetables, and all that grated liver and heart were all put back into the soup. Oh it was a real - real soup, hashey they called it. And - then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Of course you would have plenty of vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Plenty of veg - plenty of vegetables and everything, and then perhaps an apple dumpling. Or a currant dumpling. And when she made broth - it was always made by the - thick of the flank, which is brisket now. Well it was a big round piece of brisket lik
e that, I'm not exaggerating, it cost a shilling. Well the broth was made with that, it was lifted out - and if you wanted it warm with - potatoes and turnip you had it. If not it was cold for tea with - sauce or pickles. See? My father loved it with HP s
auce, it had a lovely smell and different than the meat is now, it was different tasting. Steak was different tasting. And we used to have rabbits. Of course I wouldn't eat rabbit now. But I - I loved -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Would your father bring in rabbits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 No, the cat brought them in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You ate the ones the cat brought did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well he never hurt them, he just brought them and laid them at the door. Just brought them and laid them at the door, and then - you got presents of - brace of rabbits - from peopl
e round about, or a hare. Well she always used to get one of my - father's aunts up to do the hare, the hare soup. And jugged hare. It was an awful - bother making hare soup, it's such a lot of different things to do. Never made it. Oh she used to make it
, my father loved hare soup. She used to - skin the hare. Keep its blood. And - wash it all. And she'd boil it, and before ever it was properly boiled she used to bring it down - bring it out of the pot, and the flesh, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 more flesh}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  of it she cut in cubes. And
 there was peppercorns and everything in that stock. And it was all put through sieves and rubbed through and - the rest of the meat with bones was rubbed through. And all - all that was put in the pot again. The brown hare soup, and then the blood - it h
ad to be gently stirred in to it. A lot of bother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you ever get pheasants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes, pheasants.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 From the estate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well they didn't have them there, they had shooting, but we had pheasants. We had - and then - and then we had fowl and - w
ell fish, flesh and fowl, we never were without. On a Saturday I used to have to go to - Grey that had the fish shop up here in Galloway Street. His father and mother - had a shop in the Vennel - where - Pearsons is now, at the corner of Irish Street, whe
r
e the hair - wig shop is. And I used to go - for a shillingsworth of cod steaks, and they were cod steaks, they werena the frozen - been away in the - Iceland for months. A big North Sea cod. I picked one out of the window, and that, and took the lugs off
 
it you know and bones, and one two, three, four, five, six - tail piece was split, seven. It was really eight with the other side. Cod steaks for a shilling. Well my mother - Sunday morning that - our breakfast was always - the cod steak in batter. She us
e
d to make a batter, and she had - she had a frying pan that holds seven - held seven cold steaks. Big iron - frying pan. And it was put on the sway, and the fat put in, dripping or whatever it was, and the - the cod steaks were put in. And fried lovely an
d it - oh they - they tasted lovely. My father had the big one. Three bears you know. Father and mother - brother, sister, right down. Well that was - a shilling, that cost one shilling. Five pence.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you have a different dinner on Sunday, of course
 you went to your granny's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well we had - dinner at granny's - on a Sunday, I can't remember now what we - but there were always soup, we got soup from her. Always soup first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you always have soup every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 First. Well no, my mother u
sed to make enough to last two days, and the second day it was always - better. Is that thing on? Oh better and - other days we would have - fish, haddock - and, but she used to do the haddock, the Finnan haddock in milk. And then - thicken - thicken the 
- the juice with a switched egg, and oh I loved it. Put your bread in it. And we had -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you ever get salmon out of the river?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Salmon. Fresh salmon? I don't know if I ever had - I've had the fresh salmon here but - I can't remember. Oh yes, we 
used to - trout. Trout. No. Trout. Fresh, perhaps we'd have fish - maybe in the week, and we used to have - what was the other thing we used to have, we used to have liver - mince, steak mince, steak and onions. And we had that beef soup was made of, we h
a
d fish. A - Sunday - perhaps would be a - boiled fowl. See? We always had a - a - sweet of some kind with it. And always had something for our tea, if it wasn't - black and white pudding - and they were black and white puddings in these days, nobody can m
ake them now, they forgot to put the seasoning in whatever it is that tans it I think they've left out, but - a black pudding had a distinct - flavour which it hasn't got now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 But you always got a knife and fork tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Knife and fork, knife and for
k. Then supper it was just the bread and milk. And scones, and - maybe not too many fancy cakes. A cooky, with sugar on the top, you know you sugar cookies.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 She'd buy these though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 She would buy these.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 The washing was always done at home, y
ou didn't send anything to the laundry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh no, there wasn't so much of the - laundry then, there was - were laundries but - more - cleaning - places, no, my mother never - sent anything to the laundry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Sometimes people sent away their shirts or 
even just their collars to be done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Done them all. She'd a big - fireplace, you know, down in the kitchen, and - great big-pot, like a - the shape of a fish kettle, big, and it clipped on the sway up the chimney. And she always washed her clothes tho
roughly before she even put them in the pot.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Gave them a wash through first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes. And - they were put in there and they were boiled. And - the fire irons, everything were all put away, and used to get a - what you call a coal - a shovel, you kn
ow, the - the dust pan but it was a showel, and they put in the stomach there, and lifted the - pot, and leaned the pot against that - until they lowered it to the floor.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 It would be some weight if it was full of washing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 It would be. And - then
 they were all - got the ponch stick and - they were - lifted out, put into cold water, and - she done it all by hand, wringing and everything, she didn't have a mangle or a wringer, but - up - she did - have a mangle after but at the - at this time I'm t
e
lling you about there was no mangle. And - they were all rinsed. And - I don't know how many waters, my mother was very particular about our clothes, and then - starched, collars were starched, the starch was all made up, and your little pinafores were st
arched. We had the - what they call - broderais Anglais now, we called it flowering and they were all ironed and starched and ironed and - you were always - every day you went out with a clean pinafore.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 It must have been rather difficult for your mothe
r when the water had to be carried?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
The water had to be carried, and then they had the barrels with the rain water and a tap on them you see, that you could - run it out, and - then there was the loch, well you had to bring it in - bucketfuls there, 
and - the tubs were outside on stands, and they were all rinsed from one tub to another and then - they were put in the clothes basket and hung out. Of course - we had hard winters then and we had nice summers. The weather - was quite different - than wha
t
 it is now. Wepd longer summers you knew just what we were going to be, we had storms and - things like that, and - but - it seems - things have changed now for you - you get - three kinds of weather in one day now, maybe four, and - that was the washing 
a
nd then - I had to - when I was older - I had pull the sheets with my mother and they had to be corner to corner, and - crimpled them up in your hand and pulled, your mother pulled, she nearly pulled you over you know. And - then lace curtain - they were 
a
ll - scalloped edges, well, we had to stand - put them on the line and pull every point - I was dying to get out to play you know, but we didn't get out to play until all of that curtain was straight, because - she says, if they're not straight when they'
re wet they won't be straight when they're dry. And - of course we don't have lace curtains now, so much labour saving things, but they were always lovely and crisp and clean. Then the beds -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 How about blankets? Did your mother not have a mangle for blankets?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well she got the loan of the one at the big house up in their wash house for that. But - no, well my mother could wring, she was a good wringer, she would - tramp the blankets. And - what was I going to say? Oh yes, the beds, every now and a
gain they had what they called bed pans, or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 bed curtains}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
. They were - they were washed and starched, and - they - they sometimes were flowery you know, they had - pink roses on them, and were all round the bed, hanging down like a - frill, and - they were 
swen onto the thick - on the bed. Yes, they were stitched on and they were all - when they ironed them they put them in sort of pleats. Then there was hung from the bottom of the bed. They were iron beds with brass tops, and they hung down the back of the
 
bed and hang in the front of the bed right round, and you know they were lovely. But a lot of work. But - they done them. And they had no labour saving, no - no electric irons or anything, the iron - the iron had the big - iron - black that you heated in 
the fire, and iron - my mother had the songs, slipped this thing into it, and that - kept the iron hot, and she got on with it, and all that, all the ironing, the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 collars}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  these stiff collars, they were starched shiny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Your father wouldn't wear these except on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No. Oh when he went out, when he went out. But not to - not at his work. He had the - open neck shirts, you know, not collars, but just with the stud was in here, and - he had special shirts that didn't need - ironing you see for the
 garden, they were a sort of thick - cotton, you know, and - my mother was great about her washing. Then when we moved - from Summerville, and we were in Glasgow Street, someone told my mother about the wash house, you know, on the Grange Sands. Well - do
 
you know she went there, and she loved it there, and - it was so much - different, it was labour saving and then they had the separator which we'd call a spin dryer now, that all the water was separated out of them and you could hang them out in the Grang
e Sands there where the swimming pool. Well my mother used to go every Monday - there, to the wash house. And - she used to make the whole day, I think she helped other people. When she was finished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 She just liked washing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 She liked washing, she
'd wash everything in the house. If she took the notion, just everything was taken off and was washed. And if you didn't have another one it was just put back on at night. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You say that you got the job of pulling the sheets and things like that, d
id you have any other jobs that you had to do regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Wash the dishes. Always had to wash the dinner dishes before I went to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 That would be a bit of a rush?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Ah, but I had - we done it. And then -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 How about your sisters, were the jobs sort of shared out evenly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes, of course - there was four years between and my - other sister and there there was six between the one - sister I have now, but she - she had to do her - bit too, we all had to do something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 How about your brother? He wasn't let off because he was a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No, he used to - just - I don't know what he done, but - every Friday night, see we didn't have stainless steel - we had steel knives, and the forks, and we had to clean the spoons, take the drawer
 out, clean the spoons, and - clean - the knives on a board with bath brick. And that piece at the bottom you had to rub it well in that - so there was nothing - if my mother found any food on it you - over again. Well - the only thing we had then - was -
 a paste. It wasn't Brasso. What was the name of it now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Like Gumption?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No. Well it was paste like that. But after we - had them polished - there was hot water put in a basin, some powder and they're all washed, so there would be no smell or tast
e. Globe polish was the thing, Globe polish. I can smell it now. And - then we had to shine them all again. Put clean paper in the drawer, and put all spoons and everything in. Then - the door handles - were done after that. They were all brass you see. A
n
d anything that was brass in the house my mother didn't have an awful lot of brass, was done - after spoons and knives were all cleaned. And that was every Friday night. Well ev - we had stairs that I - that - that wasn't at Summerville, that was when I c
a
me to Glasgow Street, we had to - wash the stairs. I'm brought up to work you know. Do the stairs, and scrub them, they were wooden stairs you see, down from the flat up above, and a big long - concrete passage, an outside toilet, sandstone, and a - a - a
 tub and it was all sandstone and I was to take a bit of stone round it, and put a \{BLANK\}
 round it you know. And that was - there were two people upstairs, one done it one week. Yes - and we done it another week. And that was - our job. And then there were
 stairs, wooden stairs up to the attic, all in the one place, and we had to - scrub them too. And we had the pots and pans we - had to scrub all that, put clean paper where the pots and pans were put. No labour saving things then. But it didn't do us any 
harm. Didn't do us any harm doing these things, but we were always dying to get out to play.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you get any pocket money for doing it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes. Oh yes. Oh a penny - a penny was a fortune.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Is that what you got?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Well, sometimes you got t
wo pennies. And my grandmother - she had a bank for my brother and a bank for me, and we got two pence we'd to put one penny in that bank and spend the other one. Well you could get so much for a - a penny.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you spend it on sweeties mostly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
I did, and my uncle was a - a - a confectioner and a jam boiler, we got plenty of sweets. But it was a novelty to buy them somewhere else. Something different. And you could get - oh you could get so many things for - for a penny, you could spend a farthi
ng you see in these days. You'd maybe get two aniseed balls for a farthing. And suck them through all the different colours. And a strip - a strip of licorice, you know, like braid it was, but it was licorice, they used to make tawse out of it, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 and - maybe - get a ha'penny swee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
ty watch, you know it was a watch made of - icing, like hard icing on the cakes and a chain all with a little bits. A ha'penny sweety watch, it was great. And you could - you could buy a ha'penny lucky potato, it was a - candy and it w
as rolled in - coca, and inside - maybe }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 there'd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
 be one or two would have a new penny in. And you were always going - you didn't know what to pick but if you - you'd eat it and was - oh I've got a penny in mine, a new penny. Other things. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You could spend your money on whatever you wanted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Whatever you wanted. And we had some in the bank. We had to put that in the bank. The other part of it. See? And we were always going shaking the bank at my grandmother's, now leave that alone. If you've got a;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 What happened to the money in the bank eventually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh we got it for the fair or - something else, to buy something, or when - you know, when - father Christmas - came, you know, you'd - get dips, lucky dips.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You were saying that your sisters were a good bit younger than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you have to look after them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh no. No. Oh no, my mother looked after us all, I didn't have to do anything, we just had to - every night - we'd all to be washed before we went to bed, legs, 
feet and everything. You - you had to have a - a - a bath - a bath of water or a big basin of water, and you had the sink, you know, in the sink. Well we used to sit up on that and - put our feet in the sink. Wash our knees. Wash our hands, clean our teet
h
. And my mother always done our hair. Ah, long hair, and - then in the morning we were all washed - off to school again. And our clogs or our - boots were always cleaned at night. Ready for the morning. Oh yes, I had to do that. And we used to have what t
hey call blacking. It wasn't like - anything - not like anything I know now or have seen and - we used to have to put water in it to - soften it, well instead of putting water in we used to spit in it. Oh dear. Oh well.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you have to go to bed at a special time every night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 That was regular was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes. And - my mother always every night she came in with the lamp to see that we were covered. Every night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Before she went to bed herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Before she went to bed. I can
 see her coming with the lamp - and looking at us all. Seeing maybe my sisters or me, and then - she - if the clothes were down she would put them round you, you were half sleeping. And - the younger ones she used to lift them. To put them on the - chambe
r
 - before they went to sleep, and - and - if - and she said many a time she says the - the - they - done it sleeping and then she just - sorted them and into bed again. Mother always done that, mothers well I don't know maybe some do it now. And - we alwa
ys had to say our prayers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was it your mother that heard you say them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
My mother heard them, and it was mother that learned us, if she heard anyone she learned us, we'd to say it every night 'til we got it off. Gentle Jesus meek and milk That one. We had to say that. God bless - we were taught to say our }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 prayers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
. Every night. I think it's a good thing to teach a child. But there is another being than us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 I think we talked before about you getting a bath didn't we?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes, they had - there were the public bath you see. You went -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you go there sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Then - yes, when we were older. When we were older. But - as children - a big tub and we bathed in front of the fire, and - one would be stripped, the girls were always done
 first before the boy and then - and - you were dried and - your - whatever you had clean - nightdresses to put on, and some of the water would be skimmed out and - fresh put in. And - I can see my mother carrying that bath now herself, but - out and empt
y
ing it down the sink out in the - in the - in the passage where the - the sink was. The sink wasn't in the house. It was in the house but not in the - living room. And - oh yes, we - we always had - the baths at home. But as we grew older there were publi
c
 baths down at the wash house there. And you could - oh a lot of people'll miss these baths you know, they didn't - of course - everyone - had nearly a bath in the house now. But - my father used to go to the baths. See. Have his bath there. And - oh yes,
 you could keep yourself clean.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 And you got clean clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you get a change on a Sunday or was it changed on Monday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Change - Saturday night. Saturday night. And - that was your underclothes, your underclothes all clean pu
t on, but - you'd have - you'd maybe have a - another pair of knickers or something like that, you wouldn't wear the - them all week. But your little petticoats you did. And of course you had your dresses - different kinds, if it was the summer you had th
e cotton ones.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 They would need washed oftener than your winter ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
They would need washed - yes, and your stockings were washed every night, they were black - woolly stockings, they were washed every night and hung - in the thing at the fire. The bar - rod. They were dried for the morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did your father help in the house at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You say he brought the water up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
He wat - brought the water and things like that but he - my father - no, he never washed dishes, he never do
ne anything like that. Father - and he - he'd kindle a fire. He'd kindle the fire in the morning. He would do that. And - maybe break sticks. But not housework, well that was part housework but - he always - he would light the fire but you couldn't - he w
ouldn't clean the fireplace.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 He'd bring in coal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes, and he'd take the ashes away, he'd do these things. Wouldn't make a bed, I don't think he could. And - you know, in fact - he used to ask my mother to spread his bread with the butter. And he 
was a - he had an awful sweet tooth. He loved jam, he loved sweets. And - it didn't matter what he had, we always had meat of some kind, my father must have a cup of tea and a piece of bread and jam after it. My mother used to say - I'll give you bread an
d
 jam for your dinner. He says, I don't care, he says, if I don't get a cup of tea, he says, I fall asleep, I must have a cup of tea or I fall asleep. Bread and jam after it. He was a good eater too. Of course being outside - yes, gave him a good appetite.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did he have his breakfast with you in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No. No. Maybe he came back in for it, I don't know, after we had gone. But - I don't remember my father ev - ailing anything. Never heard of him - saying he ailed anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Having a fresh air job like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
That's what it was, and - then he'd be pickled a wee bit sometimes you know, with the whisky.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 He'd need that in the winter to keep the cold out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh but he wasn't what you - he wasnae a drunkard or anything like that, he 
would just - he liked a drop of whisky. The gardener -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Would he have it in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No. Outside. You know. The only time - he had it in the house - I was just telling someone today, they were talking about Christmas puddings - well my grandmot
her - always made the Christmas puddings. She made a whole lot and they were made in - a cloth. A proper old fashioned Christmas pudding, and they were lovely. And - the week before Christmas she used to come up - with her basket with three Christmas pudd
i
ngs in it. One was for Christmas, one was for New Year, another was for after a bit. It was all over. And - my father - maybe would have a half bottle of whisky, and my mother would see it, she would just take some out of it, hide it. Well - on Christmas 
D
ay she used to make - it wasn't brandy sauce but it was just the same, it was whisky that was in it, and she made it with water, cornflour and sugar, and then she stirred the whisky in it, you know, I used to love it. I like it yet, some - just the taste 
o
f it on - on - pudding, and I know the puddings had brandy in them because - she'd been - she was a cook too, my grandmother - was, and - she - and the lovely smell of these puddings when they were boiling. Old fashioned Christmases. Oh we always had a ni
ce Christmas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 What did you do for Christmas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 We hung our stocking up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you have it all together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No, in our - in our home. We hung our - our stock - my mother used to go and get whatever she was going to get for our stockings, and -
 we didn't get any great big toys like they get now. We had - your stocking was hung up, a great big stocking that was stretched you know - and - a black - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 
woollen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  stocking, and - at the toe of it - you'd have one of yon - stockings - mesh stockings, you k
now, filled with sweets and wee - little odd things, and - you would have - oh maybe a book. Until - but I know what the top of it there was always an orange sticking out at the top. An orange and an apple, and there'd be sweets and puzzles and - things l
ike that. Oh it was the ruining of the stocking as you know. Oh what an excitement. Has Santa Clauscame yet? No. I've been up looking. We believed in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 Santa}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  Claus then you know. Oh ah. One - one - one boy used to say - there's no Santa Claus, he says. It's j
ust like your father, it's the devil. You know, we always believed in Santa Claus, but - I don't know, it didn't - that - belief - didn't do you any harm. I think it was a nice time in your life to look back on. What have they got to look back on now? Ple
nty of big toys, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you ever have dolls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes. Oh yes. Oh yes, I had dolls. I had - I had a doll - they talk about the talking dolls now, well I had one when I was in Summerville and it had a string and you pulled it and it said mama. Ma
ma. That was the first - yes, I had one. Oh and - and - then - when I got older - we - used to make - little dresses, we used to buy little penny - doll, with a china head, and the - the bodies was 'pink and they were filled with sawdust, and china feet a
nd china hands. They were only a penny. They'd be about that size. We used to make little - dresses for them, little pleated skirts, and dress them up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 It would be good practice for needlework as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes. It was, yes, oh aye. And - then at scho
ol we - we got - sewing, and knitting. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Your mother would teach you quite a lot in that way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes. Although she never - she wasn't - she didn't knit socks that ever I knew. But - my granny done them, her knitted the socks, and - I had a l
ittle - openwork - socks, horseshoe pattern. Short ones. My great aunt used to knit those. You know they were a patterned sock like a horseshoe, openwork. And - aye, and - we had always - nice shoes, strap shoes you know. And - at the school - we had knit
t
ing and your grandmother always wore garters with made of wool. They were knitted, a big long strip of just plain knitting. About that length. And she used to wind them round here, this part of her leg. They had then in - down below the knee, of course th
ey wore - the long - clothes then, and the - there - there was always put round here, on herself like, and - we used to think oh it was lovely to make - knit granny a pair of garters. And she - and when she got them she always put them on. And the -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you do this for Christmas?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes, or anytime, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
er her birthday. And - then she learnt us to knit - muffitees as they called them. Bits for the wrists, if your wrists were warm, it was just like the top of a sock, you know, plain - a rib, and you sli
pped it on in the wintertime and it kept your hands from getting chafed. And that - they went up inside your - coat. Muffitees they called them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Just to cover the wee gap?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes, and then we used to get a - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 a ree}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 l, an empty reel,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 you're your - fat
her or your mother would put four nails in the top of it, and we bought that rainbow wool, and used to start it and we had a - I think it was a pin, pin, then make these - they made these doilties, they're called doiley circles you know and sewed them all
 together. It was one long - round - sort of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 woollen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
 then that came out from under. Aye, just like that. And the nicer the wool the better it looked. Well I used to do a lot of those. Never see them now, not like that now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You had plenty to occupy yourselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh plenty to occupy, and then a book - painting, or writing, copy books, writing down - the - the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you have many games like ludo?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes. Oh yes, we had games, we had - oh yes, we always had - things like that, ludo, snakes and ladders and - all different things, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Who played with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Well, whoever was in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did your mother and father play with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
They would play - and - my uncle used to come up every Tuesday night, and his friend, and he ha
d a magic lantern. And the sheet was put up on the wall. And we had a show before we went to bed. They were all the - little - stills you know, but oh it was a thrill. He was 1 he was a photographer you see, and he used to show these - on the sheet on the
 
wall. And they'd all - some - would bring us a present or something, perhaps an engine for my brother, and my uncle always had a bag so sweets and a comic Cuts, paper. And - after that - well it was - it was say about August, my brother and I went out int
o
 the fields - and mushrooms, just at the darkening, and - oh the mushrooms that were in these fields at Summerville, see there was cattle in the fields and horses. And - just coming up through the ground, in the mist. And - I think - and my father used to
 
have the big onions, and they had - somebody would - they played dominoes they did after we wet to bed, they played dominoes, and whoever won had to pay for the supper. I used to ask my mother - she says - and they were bringing - my mother would get the 
meat or whatever it was in, and there would be fried onions and mushrooms and bacon and all these things, at night. They used to like - a feed at night.
