 to our granny, she used to take us down to the fair too at night. Granny took us there. And my grandfather - worked with horses you know, he used to - he didn't - he - he wasn't on the carts, but he was in the - the place - where the harn - the horses, a
n
d he used to do all the generals, he used to have - two big black horses that - one was called Prince, oh they were beauties, they were Belgian - horses, and - they had the special hearses then you know, not the - motor ones now, and he used to sit up on 
t
he top with his big silk hat on. Well - and then - and - in the week days, people coming in from the country, you know, say - all the landed gentry, and he used to - come to the stables there, and - he would maybe - have - take them home. Or - look after 
t
heir horses, groom their horses, while they were - ah, while they were in the town, and then - going to - balls, you know, dances, they called them balls then, and - they would - look after the horses while they were there. All the aristocrats. Well they 
u
sed to get tips. Well it'd be sixpences and three - threepenny pieces in those days. And when my grandfather came in - we were at - our grandmother - he always had a pocketful of these tips. And out would come - and he would give us all some - maybe some 
s
ixpences and some threepennies. We had to put some in the bank, keep the rest. And then - when Barber used to have the sales - he used to have - I can - he used to say to my mother the - Barber's sales on, and he'd put his hand in his pocket and I don't k
n
ow what he gave my mother but it was - sovereigns - go and get - them all something - get some - cloth - to make - coats. And he used to always buy us - shoes and boots. And he done that off his tips. He wasn't really our grandfather, was step-grandfather
.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 He must have been fond of you though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Ah. Oh he was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you have any other relations round about that you went and visited?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes, we had - cousins and aunts and cousins used to come up, we had cousins, my mother's sisters - mothe
r had - two sisters. But my uncle, he never was married, the one that was a confectioner. And then - oh yes, there were different, different ones came up, and - at the flower shows, they used to have - decorated bicycles. Well a lot of people used to come
 up with their bicycles and my father - done them all with flowers. You know even all round the - where you put your feet, and all the handlebars and all down, and you know they were lovely. All decorated with flowers. Decorated bicycles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you have a bike?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No. They were done for - men, took them to the show, they got prizes for them you see. But my father done them for them. And my father used to get - had the cup I don't know how often. At the flower shows. The cup that - his boss gave - his n
ame was first on it. It was on two or three times. The flower shows were held in the open. Out at - what's that place in the middle of the road, you know, where they -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 A bit out of the town was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 In the middle of the road, there just near the 
Crichton. You know where there was a - Wimpey houses they've built. Castle dykes, in a field at Castledykes. And of course my father - my mother used to dress us up and we always used - all went to the flower show. It was held in a big tent. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 It would be a big day for your father of course?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
It was a big day for him and other gardeners. I can see him yet coming in an open cab. Big - chrysanthemum in his - or whatever it was in his buttonhole, and a - bowler hat and a - they were dead to the w
orld. Taking out the cup he'd won, the boys filled it up. Oh yes, that was the flower shows in these days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did your father go out to many things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You say like your mother went to the Womens Guild?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 No, he - he would just go - out 
- at night for a - a week drink, and meet some of his cronies, but that was all. That was all. And - I tell you one about him. You see, the pocket money - wasn't much in these days, their money wasn't much, well - he - you could - a shilling - could last 
y
ou a week, maybe a couple - two or three glasses of beer and your tobacco. See, a shilling went like that, you see. Well Henderson, she was in Elm Bank, you know where Elm Bank is, just opposite the girls hostel, there, well - well it was a - Mintoe used 
to live in it, Wileys were in it before that, and - the lodge at the gate, well - Jimmy Henerson was the gardener there. A }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 great}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  gardener too, and - his wife, oh always used to get sixpence, my father got a shilling. And when his sixpence was finished they 
helped my father to finish his shilling. And - one night he got - he got himself cleaned up, he was always - well dressed my father was, and - he says, when he came home, he says, Teeny, he called my mother Teeny you see, do you know a funny thing happene
d
 to me tonight. He says, he was a little bit superstitious. It was a new moon, he said, and I took that shilling out of my pocket and I showed it to the moon and help me God it turned into a sixpence. My mother had taken it out and put a sixpence in. She 
l
aughed. He says - do you know anything about it? She told him what she had done. Well he says, I took it out and I had a look at it in the moonlight. He says - I'm sure I took a shilling out of my pocket, help me God, he says, it turned into a sixpence. W
e
 always used to laugh. Always used to show his money to the moon. Ah well - och And then - my father used to take us out at night - to see the Aurora Borealis when it was in the sky, the Northern Lights. Into the field, he'd say, come on out and see these
 
lights. You know it was wonderful. We always saw them up at Summerville. The Northern Lights. In a certain - of course - the - the - the Northern Lights mean that the weather's going to be stormy. These beautiful lights from the North and all they come - 
up as if somebody's opening a - a furnace, the - things coming out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you see it quite often down here then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes, yes, you could see it - in a certain time of the year in a certain place, up in Summerville, we could see the Northern Lights. The Northern Lights of old Aberdeen. Aoh aye, oh we had - we had happy times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You say it was your granny that took you to the fair though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh, aye, at - at - at night time. My granny, and we were sleeping at my granny's, she took us if the fair was there she took us down - and we -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 So you didn't have to walk all the way home in the dark?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No. So we didn't have to go home. And - the one thing I enjoyed most at the fair - was - a man used to have a little van and he cooked chips. And you
 got a - a little bagful - like that for a ha'penny. I never ever tasted - chips, of course I'm not fond of potatoes or anything now, but they were dry, and lovely and a lovely smell they had, and - on the way home she always used to buy a wee poke of chi
p
s. Just a wee - sweety bag you know. Chip - no a big paperful. And - they were dry and salt on them. They were dry. And the potatoes must have been good potatoes. They werena sli - oh I canna bear - chips, no, I - I don't like potatoes at all now. No. Oh 
yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 At Christmas did you just have your dinner in the house together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes, yes. We had crackers and - we'd every - we'd everything, some people say well - they didn't hold Christmas - in Scotland. But I said we always had Christmas, and we al
ways hang our stocking up. Always had something, and - New Year of course, my mother was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 What happened at New Year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well, at New Year - you - my mother used to bake - her cakes, and they used to be in big tins, she used to get all the fruit to
gether and - and it was all washed and we - I used to put it on trays - to dry, near the fire. Aye. On front of the fire, and she had peel and everything - I was always eating them, she said, now leave them alone, I need them. And - they were made with bu
t
ter, her cakes were. But they weren't beaten, they were rubbed in. You know, fat was rubbed into the flour and the spices - and all the different fruits, peel - candied peel, and - she got her tins all with the paper all round them. That was when we were 
i
n - what did she do when we were in Summerville, I don't know. Oh she would do - she - she - in Summerville, no, I don't know what she done there. But when we were in Glasgow Street Drummond the baker used to have a bakehouse, down at the foot of Glasgow 
S
treet where that wide - close is. And he had a - a bakers shop and a grocers shop there, and - my mother used to make the cakes, and they were all put in - in the - in the baker, and our name was put on them, and - and - and - when we came home from schoo
l
 - went down and got it, we were all frightened somebody would hit it and knock it out your hand, carrying these - my brother would have one big one and I might have another big one, and all the children, their mothers fed them - but your names was put on
 
in a piece of paper, and after the bread - had been baked, the oven - you see the fires were going down but it was just the right temperature - for a cake. Well - we took them there and we had to go back - at eight o'clock for them. And the smell was deli
c
ious. And - my father - smelt these cakes - he'd eaten the lot you know. And - she told us a story about him, she says, when she - when we lived in the Vennel, don't think I was born then, Mattier the baker down there, they had a bakehouse, and my mother 
u
sed to make her cakes and take them down - to have them baked - there, the same way. And my father come in one night, she says - oh and he wanted to eat them, she says, you're not going to eat those, she said, they're just out of the oven. And - he says w
e
ll - if I buy the stuff - will you make me one? She says, if you buy the stuff I'll show you how to make it, you can make it yourself. So - he bought the stuff, and my mother stood and showed - showed him what to do, and it was taken down stairs into this
 
bake shop, and it was cooked, and it came in - and - the lovely smell well - the ones that I remember had a lovely smell so that must have had a lovely smell too. And he got up in the middle of the night and he ate the lot. He never had a bad stomach in h
is life. He ate it, and he used to say, I can bake, I made a cake. She said, aye, and you ate it too, she says. He got up in the middle of the night and he took a long of this new cake and he ate and didn't leave off 'til he finished it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You didn't have a cake for Christmas then, you had yours for New Year?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well we had cake and all at Christmastime but - maybe somebody would send you a black bun or something like that. And we used to have that with butter on, I used to like the black buns. And th
e bakers shop that you - we got our bread in, we had - shop - they always gave us a couple of cakes of shortbread, and - Mrs Davison at the big house had ordered a cake for my mother you see. And she got that. And - Christmas - New Year time - the plate w
a
s brought out, it was on a stand and a lovely doily - crocheted doily. Then the shortbread was brought out and - put in squares, and the cake was brought out and it was cut, and all put on this. And another plate with cheese, you know, they had cheese wit
h the shortbread. Have you ever had cheese with shotbread. It - aye. And - my mother always made }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 ginger}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  wine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 The cordial?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Aye. Aye, the - yes. Yes, used to make ginger wine and we had some of that. Of course there would be a bottle of whisky I suppose for - the men and - women.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 What would the ladies drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh goodness knows, port wine I think. My mother never - took anything of that. And then tea was made and - them that didn't want wine got tea, or coffee. And - that was - New Year's 
Eve. Then there's fruit - Hogmonay, Hogmonay, seeing the New Year in. Then - of course - that was still there if anyone came in, they got a glass of whatever they wanted, and the shortbread and the currant loaf as they called it. And - if they wanted chee
s
e they had it, the cheese would be all eaten the night before I suppose. Of course - you - bought hunks of - cheese then because - you had a great big cheese dish about that - big like a great big round cheese, it was the shape of a cheese. And you put yo
ur cheese in that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 What sort of folk came in to visit you on Hogmonay then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh the gardeners from different places and your - relations, my mother's relations and - I don't know about my father's, maybe gardeners, because my father had - didn't have any brothers or sisters. He was just himself, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 What about New Years day? Did you get people coming in then too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
New Year's Day - we used to go to the loch if it - usually the ice was on the loch in these days, and we used to go there and watch skaters. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you skate yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh no, we never - I wasn't old enough to skate, every time I stepped on the ice I fell. So I - we - we - we used to put the skates - on - in the weekdays we used to - to skates were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 screwed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  the hells of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 ladies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
 shoes, and we used to get a penny for screwing the skates on. Ad - old Mr Moodie, our schoolmaster, he was a - very good skater. And there were another - one they called Yankee Palmer, he was - he was a good skater. They used to skate with
 their hands behind their back, you know, just go flying - lovely skaters they were. And then they used to have lights, torchlight - you see, at night. On the loch. A lot of people used to come up there - to the field. Then - my - father's aunt, her that 
w
as the - the cook to - that millionaire, she was - well she was bedfast nearly for twelve years with rheumatism. My mother said she used to cook such dinner, s, and then go out in the garden and to cook herself off. She says, I think that's where she got 
t
he rheumatism. But for twelve years - all the fam - she could get no further than the side of the bed, and she was huge, her fingers were like sausages you know, swollen. Well - her sister stayed with her mother, my father's - other aunt, she had been a c
o
ok too. And in big - service you know. Well - every year Sherrif Campion - used to send - he used to visit Woodbank when Mrs Scott was alive you see, and when Mrs Scott died she left - that aunt - to say she got five pound every Christmas, and a couple of
 
big - cockerels. Well - the - the other aunt had to cook these, and make the mince pies and everything, and - she gave us all a party. And she'd be at the top of the table drawn up to the bed, she could just sit on the bed with the cushions behind her. O 
w
hat a party. You got there. Oh - not half. And it was all done with the trimming and everything. Aye. My mother - used to go to Woodbank because they were allowed to - invite their friends there - to the servants hall, and they got the same food as went u
pstairs - she was the cook. And they could get drink galore if they wanted it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 There weren't many employers like that long ago were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No. He - he was as - he was a wild man though. You know, he had all his kept women in London in - in - in h
ouses, and he had - Langlands, my mother said one - one of the house in Langlands he had as a smoke room. Away from the house at all, and - his fancy ladies used to come there to see him. And Miss - Miss Scott was a lady, my mother said. My aunt had her -
 
her picture on the wall with her feathers and her frill where she was presented at court. And he was a wild man, and Sherrif Campion used to be a visitor there, and he - he could see how Mrs Scott was treated. He wasn't bad to her, but he neglected her, a
n
d he died in - poverty in America. Mm, he went through - spent - went through all his money. And - she says, many - oh she says - the - the place groaned. There was - game pies, big - Glasgow hams all cooked, you know, spiced hams and - everything. Game p
i
es and everything on the table. She says, I used to go but I was in a clothes basket - sleeping. And I couldna have been very old, don't remember. 'Cos my father was there and she - and - and there was just my brother and my granny used to have my brother
,
 and she used to take me in a clothes basket and I slept in one and everything there. One of the pantries. In a clothes basket. Oh and she says, the - food - the food was - oh, she says, you'd never see the like of it. What they dined on then. And she - M
r
s Scott darent' start the dinner until he came in. And she says, many a - time it was wasted, and Sherrif Campion would be a guest there, then he married Mrs Scott after - his death was - announced. She's got photographs and - and gave the men money for d
i
fferent photographs and - and seen that he was dead. Then - Sherrif Campion married her, but he didn't have her very long, she died. I used to see Sherrif Campion when I was maybe about ten or eleven going up the Craigs Road with her wee dog, and they say
 
he went to her grave, and he spoke to her. Anybody that's watched him form a distance, if he - he loved her. Well - when - uh huh, when - Sherrif Campion died, my - this aunt was dead, the one that - served with them, but he left the other one fifty pound
.
 Now fifty pound was fifty pound, so it must have been in her will - to do that. But every year he gave her that five pound and - and the poultry. She got it for years. Even when it - when Mrs Scott was dead he always went it to her. But - they had - oh t
h
ey - they're good times you know - as they were in those days, but not the wild - times now. You wouldn't see - women going in pubs or anything like - or a club to - there were clubs but just for men, working mens clubs you know, drinking dens, that's wha
t they were. But -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Can you tell me about other times, like the summertime when you were out to play? Who did you play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you just play with your own family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 No, oh no. A crowd - we - we knew each other, there were plenty
 - in those days everybody knew everybody, and - there were - they would help each other. Like the grown ups, the neighbours, you were all - they had no - stuck up - sort of way. Now my mother, if anybody was ill they sent for my mother. Anyone was having
 
a baby they sent for my mother. Anybody died they sent for my mother. She could do all these things. See? And anybody wasn't - very well, or maybe down on their luck, my mother would go over with something covered up, food to them, that's what the people 
were like then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Just looking after each other?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes. Well - as children, we all knew each other, and our mothers all knew each - their mothers always knew that - their mothers. And - in the summertime, the roads were very dusty. And there used to
 be a watercart came round, because we had summers and - not summers like they are now. Real hot ones, and they - they started about May, the end of May and they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 last}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  all summer. And the watercart used to have to come round to lay the dust. Well it was a s
prinkler at the back. Off came the shoes and stockings and we went behind it. The water splashing all over us. That was a great thing. The watercart. And another thing was - the - when they were carting the turnips from the fields, farmers, to another pla
c
e, farm. We used to go behind them oh and say, I wish one would fall off. And - one would fall off and you would scramble for the turnips to take the turnip to our mother. Oh - oh but this was in Glasgow street. But there were turnips, it was like everyth
ing else, they had a good taste then. And then - the - the farmer that was with the cart would never give us one each. Big - swede turnips.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you make turnip lanterns in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes, they made turnip lanterns, cut the faces in them and p
ut the candle in. And we had little black lanterns, metal ones - with a candle in. But they burned your fingers. Hallowe'en, we had them at Hallowe'en. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you get dressed up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes, be dressed up, and went out and went in - different doors,
 but nowadays they're after money. They don't want toffee and nuts and apples. Oh good, our pockets used to be all sticky with coffee and - all hair off your pocket and - ach, we used to wash it off and then eat the toffee. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 I think you told me
 earlier on that you played with one of the children from the house at Summerville, from the big house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Mr James Davidson. I - I should - should have - looked that letter out, like you to see, she wrote to me. Because - I had something in the Standar
d I told you about, Summerville, and - his cousin was - head of the solicitor - and he sent him this cutting out of the Standard, and I got this letter one day. He was Doctor Davidson by then, but he was only a little - boy, and my brother, he had a - a m
i
l cart - it was a - you know, used to wheel him about, only a pram, it was two sides of it, like a jaunting cart, but handles on it, and we used to give each other rides in this - mailcart, it was his - but we were always - whose turn it was, he - and he 
h
ad to push us. And then - he was a little red headed boy and then he had a sister Alison, she was older. She was very nice, she's dead now. And - I had this letter from Mr Davidson, and he was delighted to hear such a nice - description of Summerville, he
 
says - I remember your mother - well he was always in my mother's house, so he would remember her. And - he just played with us, he was put out in the morning and played with us, servants used to get him ready, and - he says and I also remember your fathe
r
, Billy. He says, and I remember him coming back after you left Summerville - when my father got his orchids in, he mentioned that. He said - so I always keep this letter amongst my papers, so - and he'd in Edinburgh, but he's retired now, he's a - he's a
 doctor anyway in Edinburgh Royal Infirmary. But he was a doctor - pathologist.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 What sort of age was he compared to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well - well - oh - yes, a wee bit, now wait a minute - he would only be about a couple of years or three years maybe - older than me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You played quite well together then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 Oh yes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
. Oh yes, I remember - my mother - we used to come down and we'd have a piece, he said, where did you get that? Bread and - jam. Servants gave us, Mrs Dadidson sent it. Oh. And he would have a
 great big bowl of - scrumble for strawberry jam eating it. And bread - this bread would crumble. Mrs Davidson, she wasted nothing. My mother says, what's that you're eating? Scum. Oh she says, are you. Scum. She said, all the dirt of the strawberries. An
d
 he had a basinful of - with a spoon, supping it. The three of us. Oh we used to play fine. And - when Mrs Davidson - went to - her holidays, she belonged to Lytham in St Annes, she always brought us something and brought my mother something, perhaps she'
d
 - be a little fruit spoon with - raised up fruit on it you know for - jam or sugar or anything like, that. And - or a - a glass dish, something like that she'd bring, and she brought me a doll, and she always brought my brother an engine, and she brought
 
Jimmy an engine but - Jimmy's engine wasn't as good as my brother's engine. No, that's 'cos he used to come down - said, have I the loan of the lend of Jimmy's engine? He always wanted Jimmy's engine. She says, but you've got an engine. Ah, but I want - t
hat one. And I can remember my brother trailing that engine about - thing that went in that engine. A wooden engine - with string on it, and I had a doll.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 She must have been quite interested in you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes. She was. She didn't get away with anyth
ing with my mother. You know, she was - she came down one day - asking - for - where Calder was? My mother, says, he's taken the children to see the procession. No right to go over the town in my time. My mother says, is it your time when he's out at four
 
o'clock in the morning seeing that the greenhouses are all right and the stuff's not getting frosted, she just went away no bother. My father used to say - now I wonder just to tell you what he said. My father used to say, you'd never do for a big house. 
W
ell she said she'd no right to say that because she says you're out there at four o'clock in the morning - if the frost's there, she says, you don't get paid for it do you. So - she told my father. Well he must have got a - must have - he went away up to 
t
he greenhouses to see if they still got the fire. And he must have had a bottle with him, and I think he must have gone and got a week bit tipsy. So one of the servants - said, oh, she says last night, she says, Billy came up - to the - dining room window
, and he never - my father never - said boo toa goose. And she says - I think he had a drink in him. And he says - come out you buggers now and say what you've got to say. And they were at their dinner. Nobody bothered, nobody ever said a word to him.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Your mother wouldn't stand for any nonsense?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No. Well - he had to have a drink, he had to have dutch courage. But he never said a word when my mother told him. And he would just to think to himself, well it wasn't Mr Davidson, it was her. Come out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Mr Davidson was local was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes, he was
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Maybe the fact that she was English she felt she was slightly superior?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well she - yes, she would just - but - but she was all right. She was all right. But - if she just had said that and 
that nettled my mother and it also nettled him. Oh he was going over in my time. Well he would be something by going and getting plants or something like that, different things, well he took us to see a procession I remember him taking us, and it was - it
 was a circus that came to town, and - got - I can see it now going past Barbour's shop, this big lorry, and up in the top was Britannia, on a - dressed as Britannia, and a big real lion beside her. A real live lion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 In a cage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 No. Sitting at her
 feet. Must have been a tame one out of the circus, but I see that lion now and her and - Britannia. She'd had a - something on it I suppose, it would be - tethered to the place. But the big lion, no cage, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you go to see circuses and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes, my father always took us to the circus. And he used to send us like if a thing came to - Freshwells, in a field there at Freshwell, that where the fire station is now, and - I went - used to go and see the circuses. Always took us there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was there a fair in March in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes, a March Fair, and there was the Root Fair. The Root Fair. The Root Fair was the fair, the March fair was the - of course the Root Fair was the hiring fair too for - for - people in domestic service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 And farm labourers and so on?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 But you seem to have kept yourself busy all right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
How about when you went to school, did you get different friends to play with then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Or was it just all the people from round about that went to school with you?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well, they all were from round about. That went - we went to Glasgow Street, it was a mixed school of course, boys and girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 How old were you when you started school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 I was - I wasn't four year old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 How did you start then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 I wasn't four year old, I wanted to go to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 They just let you go then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
They let me go. My brother and I used to come down from Summerville here, and there used to be a big wall across there whe
re they've made the paths now, and a big - beech tree, oh beautiful beech tree they took down from there, well that was there when we were in Summerville and my mother used to say, now you're not to be eating the beech nuts. The wee three cornered nut. We
 
did eat them of course. And we walked on that wall - we were go - when we got out of the gates - we scrambled up on the wall and walked on it - down to the school. And then we - when we - that opening - of the wall up there, that was a gate then, we used 
to come through there, a short cut instead of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 going up}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
 the avenue so we'd a field and scrambled through there - barbed wire places and onto the avenue, you know, what you do when you're children. And - oh I liked the school. And I liked -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You would get home for your dinner all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Went always home for our dinner. Yes, yes, we got home for dinner and - then back again and - that would have been - four o'clock we came out of school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You would always go back with your brother of course?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes. Yes, oh I went with him, aye. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 What were the teachers like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh they were nice, there was a - there used to be Portland Place there, there were houses there. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 There were}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  - better class houses, you know, and - better class - then there
 was better class than they're putting forth and all sorts then, but they're - they're all the same now I think, and - Miss Caxton - she was the teacher, and you know my father said - she taught him. At school, Miss Caxton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was that the infant teacher?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes. Oh yes, she - she - she taught him, he said, Miss Caxton taught me at school. There was Miss Cax - there was Mr Moodie - and there was - the attendance officer was an old - we called him Sergeant Bell, I don't know where he had - where he had 
been a sergeant in, but he was a wonderful old man. He used to wear a half - file hat, and a big long overcoat, and you know as soon as we saw Sergeant Bell it was who could get his arm to link him. And he had all us - all these children - on each arm, an
d
 he was pleasant - and - and that was an attendance officer. And he - he had - he had whiskers right round here, and his - I - I can never - find out where he was in - maybe he had been in the army, I don't know, Sergeant Bell his name was, that's all I k
n
ow about him and then there was Mr Moodie he was this - the headmaster. We'd two or three different headmasters - after that, Mr Moodie, that was him that used to go skating. And - he was always in his office like but he used to come into the class when w
e were doing our writing or our arithmetic and listen. If you done anything you shouldn't have done in the school, say you were late, you were sent to the headmaster to explain why. He was stern but he was a good -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 He was quite fair was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 What sort of things did you get into trouble for at the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Being late. Being late. You got the cane if you were late. And - a - and talking when you should have been listening. We got - you got into trouble for that and then when it
 came round for you to answer you didn't know, well you got - you got - two or three strokes on your hand. Either with a tawse or with a cane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Were the teachers fussy about the way that you spoke in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes - yes, but after we got out
 the school you just went away back into the lingo again. Ah - they do that now. Some of them are awful really. Oh yes, we had to - speak and then - you had to do your writing properly, your spelling - spelling, they were great on spelling, now they're no
t on spelling now, it doesn't matter if you can't spell. Mm. Your spelling had to be good.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Were they fussy about manners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes, and many - fuss - fussy about your manners. And - your - discipline, oh yes, discipline in the school. You had to stand to attention, things like that, and - it was a punishment if you talked you know - when you shouldn't be talking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
If you weren't quite four when you went that must have been difficult for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 What? No - well, I can't remember that part of 
it. It's as I grew older - I can remember - I always used to get pennies for my writing and - and - you were put back to back and he would call out - maybe - it would be a sum I suppose, what - what - what - what did we call that - and when you got the an
s
wer you just had to call it out. There was nobody more surprised than myself when I called it out and a got a penny. I was frightened to call it out in case it was wrong, here it was right. Composition Composition we had. Used to compose you see things, d
ifferent things and saying and you put it down and then you'd to call it out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Were all the children in this school sort of the same class as yourself? Or were there other children that were poorer than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh well, there would be - one or two, i
t was no fault of their own - you see, in the wintertime - some of these - their fathers - say they were plasterers or joiners, things like that, there was no work for the hard winters. We had hard winter - just like what we had this last week. They were 
h
ard winters, and - maybe they'd be out of a job, well there were soup kitchens - you see, for these people, there - there as no - there was no dole or anything like that, there was only parish. Parish. The parish relief, and - well - the soup kitchens wer
e
 set up and - farmers sent vegetables, potatoes - and butchers send beef, baker sent rolls, and grocers sent peas and - barley, things like that. Well there was an old Mrs Black - ran - made the soup. Now where was that soup kitchen, what was - it was - T
u
rners Stairs, it's away now, just down here, and we lived in Glasgow Street, just before you came to it. Well there are lots of children at that school went to the soup kitchen instead of going home. Well - they got - I believe they got - a big bowl of so
up, and a hunk of bread, and a big lump of meat in the soup. For a ha'penny, or a penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 That would be quite good?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
That was a midday meal - for them. And - these - I think that they done it in a big wash boiler, the soup was made in these brick b
uilt boilers, you know, they were done in that because it was - it was - it was up the Hardens Lane, I've seen - I've seen the thing, I've been in and had a look at it - like - with some - some - a girl or somebody that was going there, and - I never like
d
 the look of the soup though it was good because there was too much barley in it for me, to - it was white. It wasna like my mother's soup. But - many a - person didn't go to that soup kitchen, they came up to my mother and they got a plate of soup from m
y
 mother, cos she always made great groth. But - you used to smell, it was lovely, it smelt lovely. And then it was a good - it - it was good. It's only packet and tinned soup now unless you're prepared to make a good - pot of broth, and - well it's a - it
'
s a luxury now, making a pot of broth - Well it was always made with beef when my mother made it. And - they - that was a great help in this town in these days. Was the soup kitchen. Because there was - lot of what they call poor people, but they were res
pectable decent people. There was a few - scallywags but - they didn't count, but - the children - couldn't help it could they. But they - they - we were all at the school together, we all knew each other.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you find that the teachers made any pets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No, I don't think so, I don't know. But - we had a Miss Watson, and - she was a nice teacher. Oh - there's one - there's one teacher now - and I see her and she taught me, and she's a - she's a Miss - Robertson, her - her - her people had a - a drap
ers shop in Buccleugh Street where Barr is now. And - oh she was a bonny girl and - long fair hair, she must have been about - well she - she couldn't be sixteen, she couldn't have been much younger if she was a pupil teacher could she. Well she's still g
oing about. And - I knew her as soon as I saw her, and she always gives me}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525  a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  wee smile and I - I never like to say to her, maybe she doesna like the - me to say that she taught me. But - she - I don't know, she - she looks - she - I see her in the Post Offi
ce when I go in she's in her for her pension and I'm in for mine. Said, she used to teach me. Pupil teacher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 How old were you when you finished school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Beg pardon? Fifteen. I could have stayed on longer. I - I - was in the supplementary - no, th
e - the supplementary - down here - a qualifying - I was in a qualifying class and then - I passed and it went to Lorinau. I went to Laurinau, well we'd a few masters - different masters there, well we had one master - a Mr McLeod and after school hours -
 
he asked who would stay behind and he'd teach us French or Latin, whichever we wanted. Well they used to have French lessons there - through them all - beside - you - you didn't want the school, I didn't, anyway, I was always wanted to leave, and - you go
t so far with these lessons and - and then - the night classes, you learned the shorthand and typewriting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you do that too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well I did for a little while. Mm. Might as well not - I never took it up. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You never know when it might come in handy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Ah that's true. However -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was your family musical at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you have any musical instruments in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh melodian. I don't know who played that now. It wasn't me. But my mother's brothers were all m
usical. My mother's brothers could sing and - that and my - and my brother when he was a - he's dead now - he was a lovely singer, my brother was. And one of - my mother's - nephews were dancers. Singers. Went into concerts singing - these days. Uh huh.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You never had musical evenings in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh if anybody came in and they could sing my father - they never got out again till they'd sung two or three Bruns's songs. He loved Burns songs. Loved Burns songs. And - people could sing, come on, you
're going to - sing me a song before you go. He used to - like My Love is like a Red Red Rose, he loved that song. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was there Burns clubs in the town in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes. Burns suppers. Oh - my father used to go to the Burns suppers, alwa
ys a Burns supper, and - it was in the Salutation - aye, and I don't know - Steel were the name of the people that were in it then I think - and he always used to get old Mrs Steel, Jean Steel they called her - he used to - she always used to keep the she
e
p heads for him, that's for the sheep head broth. Wasna the sheep head - for the - that was for the - the cats, the meat on it, but it was for the tongues. Well she used to wrap all the sheep heads up in a paper and he'd go home - with a great paper full 
o
f sheep heads. But mother says - what are they for - he said, it's for the tongues, so when he was in his bed sleeping she took the tongues out, and put them in a plate and put them away in the cupboard. And he came - and he got to have a look in the morn
ing, he looked in every one of them, he says, they're all dummies. All dummies. So this - then the sheep tongues were cut up the next day, we all had them. Quite good, she pressed them into a basin. She - they were all dummies.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Do you know what happened at Burns suppers in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh there was - oh yes, just like a musical evening. Toasting, drinking, of course my mother never was at them, my father used to go to them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was it always just the men then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Well, it was more men than wome
n went then. Jolly old - beggars you know. Like Burn. Oh my father used to love a Burns supper. Used to go to them. Oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was your father }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 interested}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  in politics at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Well - I think he was Liberal, I don't know but as there were just Libera
l and Tories then. My mother was Liberal, no, my father was a Tory.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 That would make for some arguments in the house then did it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Mother - mother was Liberal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
What did your parents think about swearing, you say your father took a drink sometimes
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did he swear at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes, sometimes he did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did he allow you to swear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh no. No. But my mother - says when she - she says, when I was - oh very small, don't know how old I was, I can't remember it - and she sa
id it was at Summerville, and she says - we were having soup at the table and this great aunt of mine was at the table and - and I took a spoonful of soup, and - it must have been hot, and she says, you just said, oh hell, I've burnt my moustache. She sai
d - oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 What happened to you after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 I don't know, I think everybody just went silent, she said.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Your great aunt wouldn't approve of that likely?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No. So - I don't know - whether - I can't remember ever saying anything more. And wh
at I seen - once I did - in the house say something, my mother said, well - she said you were swearing when you were three year old, and she told me about this, what I'd said at the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 If grown ups were speaking were you allowed to join in the conversation?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh no. No. And when my mother - took us out - to visit anybody, she says, now - nowadays the children are poking here and they're poking there. There's no - discipline. And - we used to stand by my mother's side. We must have been wee porr
it mice mustn't we. But - we were - we was told not to - touch anything in anybody else's house, we were - we were taught our manners, and my mother - was - speaking to somebody once about her - her children were in the house and they were just wee pests,
 
had everything down off shelves and everything, and mother says, well, she said, I never allowed mine to do that, she says, I could take them anywhere. She says, your - your children must have been angels. Well, she said, when I look round about she says 
they were. She said, when I look round about they were angels.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 If you did do anything wrong?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh you were punished. Yes. If you done anything you shouldn't have done - you're - told a lie, you were - aye, you got into trouble. Or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was your mother always fussy about you telling the truth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes, but - who always tells the truth? We've all told a lie in our life I suppose just to get something. But - oh - we weren't too bad really. But we weren't allowed to cheek anybody. Weren't allowe
d to speak back to anybody, I don't know whether that was right or not, I don't know. You can speak back now if you want. But - we were - we were brought up - to respect other people, and other people's property. I don't - I don't think there's vandalism,
 
so much vandalism, there might have been mischief, but there were no vandalism - as it is today. And people were different. People - they'd hearts of gold some of these people that weren't too well off. They were really. And it - good neighbours. Good nei
ghbours. And they lived in hovels.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 But you didn't need to have money to be good and kind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh no, no, it wasn't - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Do you think you got your ideas most from your mother or from your father? About how to behave?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh I don't know, my fa
ther you know - was my - my father wouldn't let us do just as we liked you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 He certainly seems to have been a bit softer than your mother though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes, he was, my mother - we had - we had to - respect - other people, and we had to talk back.
 When I always used to - do the shopping, the messages, and go to the butchers - oh I've got that thing cut out of the paper for you by the way, and - the butchers, and we never asked for - mince, said don't you just say half pound of mince or whatever we
 
would be buying. Get half pound of steak or a pound of steak or whatever it was, and then ask him to put it through the miner. I don't want that mince that's in the window. And - or you'll be sent back with it. Well that was one thing I hated was to take 
anything back to a shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you have to do it sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh I hated to go back with it. But if it wasn't right we were sent back. And - we had to ask for the steak and then ask him to mince it, she said, don't want that stuff they mince up and p
ut on a plate. And - oh - I was learned to do shopping, and learned what was - that and we were sent for fish, say - haddock, I don't know if I said that before - we had - turn it - used to have to tell the man to turn it over to see it was haddock and no
t whiting. She says - finger and thumb at the back told you it was haddock. So I always remember that. Always remember that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you do most of the shopping for your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 I used to do a lot of shopping, ah, I used to do a lot of things you kn
ow what - my mother couldn't come out, and I was at school, used to go down the street and get - of course she always had her order sent from - from - Gibsons in the Vennel, for years. But - any little ods and ends you - you think you've got all you want 
i
n the house and then when you look round you haven't, you've something you've - missed out. I used to have to get it as I came out of school. I'd learned to - and that you learnt you to count your money. So of course nowadays the money's different. Can't 
count it, it's away before you get time to count it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Did you find that your mother was an easy sort of person to speak to when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 If you had done wrong you wouldn't be frightened to go and tell her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Ah - no. No. Oh no. Oh my mother never - my mother was good - was a good mother. And she was jolly - too. She got on with people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 She seems to have been a good manager anyway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes, she managed enough on what she had. She did, I don't know how
 she done it. She kept us all. Clean. And - fed, we never went without anything like - we were - didn't live not - no extravagances you know, anything like that. If we couldn't get a thing we'd to do without it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 How about your father, you were quite close to him when you were a child?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes, oh yes, oh yes, my father we used to - oh I used to think a lot of father you know - quite close then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
A lot of people in that time, their fathers didn't really take very much to do with the children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh aye, but my - my father - oh yes, my father was interested in us and - and we done anything we shouldn't have done he would just - tell us, shout at us or something. And he would say to my mother - see to her, or see to him, you know. Oh mother was
 the one. Aye. Spank you, well - it was - it - it was - it was - he was hopeless in the house - getting a meal, he could make a cup of tea I suppose.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 But he was good at his job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Well in his job, in his job, oh yes, he was one - he was a fine ga
rdener. And - a very good gardener, fine at his job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Do you remember any funerals in the family when you were wee like that?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Funerals? No, I don't know. We were all grown up my sister was the first one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 I was wondering maybe about your great aunt?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Ah well, yes, I think - it didn't - it didn't - upset you so much - then, you were young, and you - well - at the time - you felt like they'd gone, but - you didn't have the emotion - that you'd have now. You were too young to realize, of cou
rse it's not given us to grieve when we're that age is it. It's when you get older. You recover quickly. And but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 What about funerals then, did women go to the funerals then or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 No. No. I don't - when anybody died like that you - you - you 
didn't go to anything, they - I mean somebody looked after you till it was over. But - my granny I think was the first one, of course I was - I would be about - what would I be then? I'd be about eighteen I think when my grandmother died you see. But - yo
u
 weren't just so emotionally upset - in those days, because your life was just beginning then wasn't it. Your - all your life like. And you didn't think - you'd maybe think after well, I can't go to my granny's now, she's away. Your mother - and father wa
s more like to miss them more, likely ones to miss them, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Children adjust more quickly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes. I - I can't remember no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Do you think you and your brother went to Sunday school together, did you go on any Sunday school trips?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes,
 always went to Sunday school trips. Aye, we went to Lochanhead. Aye, the Brewell, by foot. And - come along and Castle - is that Comewell Castle. Yes. And - we always went on the train. No, we didn't go -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You didn't go in a farm cart?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 No. No. O
h no. We went on the train. And - my mother used to go, my grandmother used to go. The whole family went and we had - oh we had - Greyfriars church I belonged to then, it was - old Mr Weir, the Rote Mr Weir and his wife. -Oh she was a lovely woman her. Sh
e
 used to gather us all round, she says, and how are all my little children today? And she'd just come like an old hen you know come round you. She had no family of their own, I forget how many years they were in Greygriars church. He baptised me. And - I 
think - I think my mother was - married by Mr. Weir too.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was your father a churchgoer as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No, he wasn't. But latterly - he went - when Mr Wilson was at - took queer - Mr Wilson and - and my brother belonged to - Torquery, he was in the choi
r at Torqueer, and - Wilson the minister used to - he was a great gardener and farmer as well as a minister, he was. Yes, well he used to come to the nursery up here for his plants and my father thought an awful lot of him. So my brother said - Wilson's g
o
ing to preach about so and so today, you want to come? Amazed my father - of course, when he was young - he did go, he was at - at Tolmachy, he went to the church there but they were all these country people, never missed the church did they, and - he wen
t
 - to - Mr Weir - Mr - Wilson, and he thoroughly enjoyed him and you know, when my father - died - he - two or three times he went there, my father died - my brother says, I think I'll get the Reverend Jone to - take the service, because he was the only o
ne he was ever interested in, and he did. Yes, oh he thought - and what a - I remember that day, he said that - he was fond of beautiful things, you know, flowers and everything. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 And he}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  spoke so well, of course he was himself, he was a great outside man wit
h the - John Wilson. In fact his wife - she's alive, she's in Johnson Trust Houses, she's a great artist, but - Mrs Wilson. In Johnson Trust Houses. Of course that's away from what you were asking me. Yes, I went to the Sunday school trips.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You were saying your brother sang in the choir, were you ever in the choir?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 No, not me. No. No. Not me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Anything else connected with the church, like Band of Hope?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well no, there was no - I don't remember them having - there were - there weren't Ban
d of Hopes different places, we used to go and - and - and - a missionary would come and you know we used to sing all the different - I'm H-A-P-PLY. We used to get a little shield - God is Love you know, stuck on the wall and we were always so pleased to 
t
ake it home, little blue with silver letters, and all these - different little things. And you know - we went in evenings, and the crowd, and we used to clap our hands, I'm H-A-P-P-Y, I'm H-A-P-P-Y, but you really - we didn't run wild. Not as they do now.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Were there Guides or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No, I wasn't in anything like that, no. No. I wasn't in anything like that, just went to - we - went to the church Sunday morning, my brother and I when we came from Summerville, and - we used to pass whe
re you could go down to my granny's then it was the - the Brewery Steps, that's just where - you know where the - Oliver's flower shop is and then there's that stretch of forecourt now, it was a brewery there, and there were steps down it, you got onto Br
e
wery Street, but we didn't call as we were going to church, we went to church. After we came out - we came - went down the Brewery Steps, to my granny's. And there we had our dinner. Then she got as all ready for the Sunday school. Greyfriars Sunday schoo
l.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Your Sunday school was in the afternoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
In the afternoon. Then we came back, at night with her, she used to go to that great aunt's of mine or to another friend, we knew we - just where to find her, and we had our tea. And we accompanied her
 to Marshaltown West, so we were well churched, And she brought us home to Summerville. Always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 So you were going to two different churches?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Aye, well that was her church you see. Marshaltown West.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 And when you started going to church yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Greyfriars. Greyfriars. I was married by the Greyfriars minister too. Oh I was christened in Grey - well, by the Greyfriars minister, I'm not so much christened in church then it was done at home. Uh huh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You were christened at home were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes. Yes. We were all christened at home I think. There weren't so much of going to the church carrying them then. No, I don't think anybody ever went like that. Really. They were christened at home. I was christened with the water out of Babin
gton Loch. My mother used to keep a little dish that she had - and when my brother, he was born in Glasgow Street and - my father went up and got a bottleful of the water out of Babington Loch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 There's no such thing now is there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 No
w we come to when you were finished with school and starting to work, did you ever do any wee jobs before you left the school that you got paid for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes. The shop that I went - my uncle's shop I went - morning and night, to take any parcels to anybody that - from the shop, a message.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 That was the one that had the sweetie shop?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes. And - and it was a - vegetables and - and - and - fruit and vegetable and confectioner but then it was at Nith Place where Blunt the chemist is now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 That was quite a bit away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes, well I used to go in the mornings. Maybe for half an hour. Somebody maybe just lived at maybe at the Craigsor Road or somewhere, and - then at night after I finished school. I went - they seemed to have - be long evenings, t
hen, long summers, good summers. And - I got one and six a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 That wasn't too bad considering?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
And my brother used to go with the milk cans you know. Deliver the milk. That was in the mornings. I think he had one and six a week. Well - it - i
t always helped to - cauker your clogs or - mend your boots. It was a lot, one and six was a lot then you know compared to what - things are}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You left school when you were fifteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Fifteen, yes. And - I went -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was there ever any doubt about what you were going to work at?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well I didn't - I really didn't know what I was going to do really. At - the first thing I tried was - in Gibsons factory up - the Cauberry hill, with - that's where you had a machine and you made - put the fingers into gloves, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 woollen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  gloves which they do now. I didn't like it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 I haven't heard of that factory before.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh it's finished now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was it quite a small one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Ah, was - wasn't as big as McGeorge's, just there at - it - it's still there I 
think the council use it as a workshop. They made - they made - these - honeycomb gloves, you know, with the honeycomb hands and - honeycomb fingers, but that was a big machine and the - women worked on these. But this was a small machine - went back and 
forward to it, and picked it up. But oh - I had ever so many stiff necks, it must have been with doing that. I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was it a well paid job or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well you got so much - you got so much - for every dozen gloves that you fingered, you'd to fit four f
ingers and a thumb, and - just run them - they went out to people outside that used to - sew them. Finish them off, put - pick the stitches up and I - I don't know what they got, slavery I think - for doing those things. Then they had a spinning house whe
r
e you used to take your bobbin - you know the way you get the bobbins now with the wool on - you took your - your hanks of wool, there was a cupboard you used to go to it and you used to - olive oil, and used to rub your hands all with olive oil and oil y
our wool. And take it over to the - spinning house, and that was put on a bobbin. Then you came to your machine and - you - some sort you know their nose was in it the whole day but mine wasn't. My mother used to say, you'll never make \{BLANK\}
 And - my uncle said that -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Why did you go there in the first place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh I just - you know, I wanted to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you get fixed up with jobs at the school or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No - no, I didn't - I didn't - I don't know - we learned French and all things like tha
t but I just didn't want to know. You know. So - my uncle - or my mother he was wanting somebody in the shop, to learn - the counter. So I went in. And - yes. And gradually I - I think I was there for about seven years. Then I got married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you find it a drawback working for a relation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No. No, he was very good - no, he was - a confectioner and jam boiler, the place has gone now, it was in Lorburn Street, and he was the head one in there. He was a confectioner and jam maker, it was Johnson - t
he grocer, the wholesale grocers, and there was - my uncle, a woman and a girl, and I - and when I used to go up there - to ask him things, you see, I had the keys of the shop - after I got to know - everything I opened the shop myself you see, and anythi
n
g I wanted just had to tell him and - and he made - he made sweets in the house and all for the shop too, tablet and all that - these sort of things. And - I used to go up there - and a great big - copper pans, jam boiling in them, and if it was - the was
ps, season of wasps was all up my uncle arms and - I never knew how he did - never got stung. The wasps were all up here eating the jam in the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Maybe because he didn't try to knock them off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 He never bothered about them. I used to run out, I was
 frightened. And - then we watched him making the sweets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 I thought in those days most people would have made their own jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh it went to grocers shops you see, it was good jam. It was just like homemade, big jars, two pound jars, oh these - yo
u'll never see a two pound jar of jam now do you? And - it was real good jam. They didn't make an awful lot, but what they made went - to different big grocers shops, I think that's where it went anyway, and then had the bottles of sweets, black balls, ci
n
namon balls - and you - mixtures, fishes and stars and things. And you had little - machines - on this - had a great long slab, it was - it's slate, where they used to roll all the sweets in - in butter on - on that, roll the balls like that and then - ri
d
dles and riddled them, then they got a great lump of toffee round their nail and pulled it, and a great big flat piece of - wallopy toffee, and that - these are little - brass mangles, and it went in, it come out stars and fishes and all sorts of things. 
Before it - started to harden you see. And it was all in the - slates, and - and then sugar put over them and then they were all bottled. And they were sent out to different places, well they used to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 sell}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  them in the shop that we were in. And seven pound ja
rs of - mixtures and they were pure sweets.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you not find it a great temptation working in a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 place like}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Well, at the beginning - you - sampled - chocolates that came in I think and knew every centre. My - it was Rowntrees Imperials the
n and Cransons and - not so many - Cadburys and Frys. And - then different - people used to make - sweets. And - the first war - during the first war there was a new - a new company what they called the Continental Chocolate. Oh it was the best chocolate 
I
 ever tasted. Continental, well we used to sell an awful lot of - and - boxes of chocolates and - it was a good sweet shop. All at once - he said, I wonder what's happened to the Continental traveller, he's never been. It came out that there had - built a
 
factory in Ed - in Edinburgh, and underneath it was all fixed up with guns, they were from Germany. Mm hm. And they found - they got them and found it. And started up a chocolate factory. This was a blind. Lovely chocolate. Yes. So - oh - and that was in 
the first war. They were - they were getting ready to go for Edinburgh Castle I think, something like that you see and they were near - and all underneath they said it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 all cemented}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  with guns mounted on it and everything all under - supposed to be a choc
olate factory. Which it was. Ah well I - heard that. But it disappeared. Went right off. And - my uncle used to say - if you want anything just take it, eat it, you'll soon get sick of it, which is true. You didn't want it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 How about the fruit and vegetables, did you have to buy them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
He bought them, my uncle, he done the buy - he done the buying. And I done the paying, he used to leave his cheque book with me, blank. He could - he said, I can't be bothered with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 travellers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 , just see what they wan
t. Yes, I had the cheque book in the shop for them coming, and - signed with his name like but open. Ah, fill in the money. He used to buy about fifty barrels of grapes at a time you know, they would give him - give him a - a - a price, and - well - he di
d
n't know whether he was buying a pig in a poke or not, he just took them, perhaps he would have fifty good barrels of grapes, beautiful Almeria grapes, they were in the - that cork - dust - cork in barrels. And he might have had - oh - maybe half a dozen 
b
ad ones. You know, he wouldn't get - just as he pulled them out they were - mostly rotten on the stalk. But other ones when they were good they was good. But he - seemed to - do all right, and he used to - have a buyer in Covent Garden to buy fruit for hi
m
. It came by rail, and it paid him he said to do that. Got the fresh fruit. Mm hm. From Covent Garden. Uh huh. Oh - oh yes, I liked - I liked that shop and then he went to one in the High Street, which is going to be demolished soon, it's a disgrace, I wo
uldn't go in it now, and - he put a new front in it, he bought that shop and put a new front in it. Double windows. I was there for a few years. But no vegetables there, it was just fruit and confectionery. That was my work, my trade, and I liked it.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You enjoyed it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You didn't have any regrets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh no, I never - no, no. As longs as I could count. But - that was - then I met my husband. I was going to the bank when I met him, with the money. I used to take the money to - to the bank
, he used to make it all up at - in his own home you see, put it in the leather bag and I used to take it every Monday morning up to the bank in English Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was it his idea or yours that you should go and work there do you think?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 His I think
. Aye, asked my mother and I - I - well I though, yes, as good as anything that was going then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 When you started working did you give all your pay to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes. Sixteen shilling a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 That was quite good was it not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 I had sixteen shilling a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Your father wasn't earning all that much more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No. And - I had to buy my own - my mother had to buy my own overalls, but I used to get them made from the little shop opposite - the shop that I was in in Nith Place. And -
 you were always tearing them, you know, on a barrel, or on a - nail in a box. Aye. Oh I used to like a new - it - we were always very busy. Saturday night, you'd your customers and you had your - passers by. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 What sort of hours did you have to work?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Ah - eight - eight o'clock in the morning - until eight at night. And on a Saturday it was eleven. Eleven o'clock at night. Then it came to nine. Eleven o'clock at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 And you got customers even at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes, you got customers
. You got custom - you got - you got them coming from the pubs, they spent more money than anybody. You got customers - and - then it came that, you know, the shop rules, nine o'clock on a Saturday. Well - my uncle used to provide - the bread and - meat, 
t
ins of meat or so - I think it would be and - and - butter, sugar and tea, everything, and I used to have to make the sandwiches, and - it was either coffee or tea or whatever it was, and at about - when you worked late - late - about nine o'clock I used 
to make - for - 'cos you used to have two or three more people in on a Saturday night, you see, they were so busy. And - I would make that in the little - place we had at the back. We just took it in relays to - come and get it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you get home for your dinner in the middle of the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes. Oh went home for my dinner. Home for my dinner and home for my tea. But he used to say, now - if you're - if you want - if you're going to make yourself }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 some tea}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 , he says, and you want anything, cakes or an
ything, just take the money out of the till, and put a note in how much you've taken out. He was - that's what he was like. As long as you put the note in to say how much you've taken out, he says, that's all right. He said, I don't mind what you buy, as 
long as you put a note there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Do you reckon that he was like that because you were family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No. He done it to - aye, aye, that was the way, and he used to say, now - when you're serving the sweets or anything or - tablet or anything, he says, if t
he scale goes down with a bang don't - bang, don't take it off, just leave it. It'll come back. And if you want a sweet eat it, you'll soon get sick of it. We were never forbidden to eat the sweet. Some of these places you're in you know you couldn't eat 
a
 sweet, they take - they took stock - in the morning, my sister was at Newtons for a while, and they used to sell these - that was in - it was Old that owns the shop and good baker there, a high class place it was, used to sell Moirs of Canada - chocolate
s
. They were never - they weren't known hardly, and - she said, oh it was awful, in the morning you got the - big boxes - open - like a - maybe about four pound or five pound, and they were weighed. And - there was no chance of you eating one of those. The
n
 at night after - you finished, what was left was weighed, and your till had to correspond with what was come out of that box. So they had to take one now off that it - just balanced, if it went down he used to say don't take it off. You'll get custom. Br
ing them back. That was his idea. And used to get the barrels of apples and - I used to - window dressing, I used to do the window, all in - and the grapes and bananas were all hung up you know and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Like at Christmas time did you do baskets of fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes. Yes. Mm hm. Oh yes. And - we were always busy, and then when - when - then it came to eight o'clock, you stopped at eight o'clock. Well he always used to come in himself - and we got away and he locked up. He had the stray customer, he had noth
ing else to do after that like. Stay in the shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
What did you do in your spare time in those days, but you wouldn't have all that much spare time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Not much spare time. I was happy in it, I was really happy in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 By the time that you finished at eight and got home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You wouldn't feel like getting changed and going out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Of course you had your - you had your - an hour or so off, no - no, not at that time, of course - it was eight o'clock at night - that you were finished,
 well - time - wasn't like what it is now, there weren't all these - things to do, you could go home and - you had some work to do at home, clean the spoons or do something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You still had to carry on with your jobs did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you go out with your friends at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes, oh yes, we went out, I used to meet my - friend at - you know, came - when we're coming out of the shop. Well there was plenty of places we could go, we could go to a little caf\'e9, we could go - to the pictures, second house. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Did you keep the same friends that you'd had when you were at school or did you find you made new friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh I made new friends. I made new friends, and - some}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 them that I knew at the school of cours
e used to come into the shop. Buy they - most of them went working in a factory. See, it was either shop or a factory. Then, not - not in an office.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 The factories started earlier in the morning and finished earlier at night?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes, the mills an
d that, there was the mills too you see, we used to get a lot of mill folk - going to their work buying sweets. Coming in for their sweets in the morning, they sometimes started - they started at six o'clock the mills and then they come home for their - b
r
eakfast, and - went back at nine. So one - then when they got off one to two, and then they went back and they finished at six o'clock at night. In these Rushfield Mills across the water there they were - they were - thriving places then, tweed mills. I u
s
ed to see the women going - knitting all the way, knitting, walking to their - aye, walking to their work, knitting socks. And they'd to go up that suspension brae to get to that - mill. And they were with - with all their shawls on and their clogs. And t
he suspension bridge - when we - were at the school we used to - know when the mill folk were coming - home, get on the suspension bridge and it swayed - with the people that was on it. Mm hm. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you ever do any work after you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No. No. No. I went back to the shop - there was someone left, I went back to the shop when we were - but my husband was away you see. And we weren't like settled down. But I wasn't long - there 'til I came home again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 It was just to help out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes, it was to help out. But I did - I never - took another job, unless it was just a temporary job, during the - during the - the - last war there - I was in Porthelly, well - the fire station, the girl that lived next door, she made the dinners for the 
firemen. Well she was going on a holiday and she asked me if I would take it. Of course my daughter, she was at home with my mother and I - and I used to go - for a fortnight I went there. I usually had the dinner ready when the fire}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 bell went. Had to keep 
it - warm - of course. They bought the stuff and I made it and it was rationed and I had to take something out - off everybody's ration to make them a - a sweet, a pudding or anything like that and they used to always bring - steak or something in and a f
r
uit, the - the vegetable, and - I made them a dinner, whatever - they wanted. And then I went round all their rations and took a bit of marg a bit of - sugar and a bit of - and make them a steamed pudding and - they were quite pleased - that I - and what 
w
as left I used to put - there's some bits left over I used to put it after they washed up, put it in the - their cupboard. I said, what happened to that I put in? Oh big mouth ate it. You know, one of them. I said, well, as long - it was all right. They m
a
de their own breakfast but I had to wash the dishes. And left them there. However it was - I wasn't so busy, I got plenty of time to do it, and they went and got the - stuff for me. But the big heavy - pots and pans you know. I used to make - have to make
 a big potful, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 p}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
otatoes and - vegetables, stewed steak and onions and - the meat was rationed but not too bad, it wasn't like what it is now, it wasn't rationed by price. Its rationed now by price. That was the only -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 To go back to when you started wor
king there, was Sunday any different after that? You wouldn't be going to Sunday school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No, but we'd to go to the church, Sunday was a long day, didn't know what to do with yourself. My - I had a chum there - I used to go to her house, and - perhap
s I'd have my tea at her house then, you know, now and again. But - I think - she was mostly at our house - for - her tea, it was an open house our house was, my mother's. The more she had in it the happier she was. But we always - then we would go - the 
church at night. Going to church at night. Oh and - sometimes you would go a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you go to church in the morning too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes, yes. And - go a walk in the afternoon. Perhaps away up the Fishers Lodge or some of these places, you just had to make your own a - amusement you know. And - perhaps you'd meet a few boys, you know, and - you just didn't walk about like dummies,

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You would go out in a crowd would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Out in a crowd, oh yes, we kept the crowd, we didn't separate. Crowd of boys and 
a crowd of girls, and - my - my - chum, she died when she was - twenty-three, she wasn't in very good health I think it was - consumption she had, and - she was my best maid of course at my wedding, and she just went into a sort of decline. They were a gr
e
at big - a big family of them. Family. I think the father - old Mr Allen, he was insurance - supervisor, I think he had - don't know how many wives he had, but - she - she took me one day to St Micheals cem - churchyard, and a headstone there, and I think
 it had about twenty-four to have a family, between his different wives, and my mother used to say, well no wonder Jenny's not - healthy, she says, after all these. After all the big family that they had. And a lot of them died in infancy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 They just wouldn't have the chance that a smaller family would have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Mm hm. But she lived on. I remember her going in our house, he always used to keep his own room, oh he was a - funny old beggar, and he used to come out and - when Jenny was going out with me, 
he said, Janet - are - you've got plenty of clothes on? Are you keeping yourself warm? And used to have to take his food into that room too him. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Wouldn't he eat with the rest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 No, he never came amongst the rest. However -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You mentioned about you went out with a crowd of boys and girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Aye, we all went out with -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 How old would you be before you started going out with a boy on your own?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh - oh - I never bothered about - I was - I was sixteen - and I never bothered about
 boys, you didn't bother about them. Just - well, went past and that was the end of it. But - as you got older - you'd go out perhaps with - a boy and - and ask - he would ask to see you again and you just look and them and say, ah no. No. You were - fanc
y free, you didn't fall in love with them as they do now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did your mother or your father want to know who you were going out with?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 I suppose they would know most of the folk in the town?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 In the daylight they didn't mind
 perhaps you'd stand with a boy - perhaps I was about - eighteen or nineteen then - and my father used to go past and look at me. My mother would say, who was that you were with tonight? I'd say, so and so. So and so. She says - she says, your father has 
s
aid - who's that she's standing with tonight, it's not the same one she was standing with last night. I never - you never used to bother much about it, all he - all he bothered - himself about - did you get a box of chocolates? And I never ate chocolate b
eing in the shop, and he got it, that was the only - did you get a box of chocolates? 'Cos many a box of chocolates I did get.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 That was the done thing was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes. Yes. Yes. Uh huh. It was all quite innocent, not like what it is - I wouldn't like to - have a girl - these - in these day - this day and age. It's - the life's so different.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You would go for a walk or go to the pictures?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes, of course - there were - you weren't just - trumps or anything like that, there was - normal. 'Til you met the right one. That was the main thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You say you met your right one going to the bank?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Going to the bank. Ah.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 How old would you be then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
I was - twenty. Twenty. And - I don't think I was twenty - between nineteen and twen
ty. But I just - I was just - he was just here and following me and he waved at me across the street, I said, oh who's that - to myself. And when I got to the bottom of the street I turns round and looked, and he had his - I couldn't make any - the unifor
m you know and I couldn't - I don't know who that is.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you know him before that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No. It - he was - eight years older than me. I'd been at the school where his brother though, he did belong to Dumfries but he was in the Flying Corps. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 So he would possibly know you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No, he didn't know who I was from Adam. He used to come - stand with a crowd of fellows at the shop in Ninth Place and I said I wonder who that fellow - there he is over there. He used to always be popping up you know 
where I was. At last he walked into the shop, and asked me my name. That was in Ninth Place shop. And he was on six weeks furlough as they call it, didn't know whether they would stay or not. He was staying with - people, when his father and mother died y
o
u see - they were all scattered, and he went to live with these people and he was with the son of the - woman he stayed with, that morning that I met him. I knew the fellow he was with. So he was just - they all scattered and lived with aunties or somethi
ng like that. Well - his - mother died when she was thirty-seven. And his father died two years after, forty-two, then there was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 There must have been quite a young family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 He was the eldest, he joined the army, went away. He used -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 He was in the army first before he went into the Flying Corps?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes, he was in the Kings - Kings Own Scottish Borderers. He was stationed in Ireland, I didn't know him then but he told me about it. And - he used to - he was on the reserve and he drove for Colonel Todhunter, he was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 chauffeur}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
 out there and then he left him and joined the - the - RFC. So he done all that time, nine years a Kings Own Scottish Borderers, I didn't know him then, but I knew who the family because I - his brother - had been at school with his brother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
What was it like in these days, did you take your boyfriend home with you to meet your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes, used to see - well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did your mother want to have a look at him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Yes, have a look at him. Oh your mother - I 
don't know - they needn't have been frightened in those days but I should think they'd be frightened now. But - I always remember, this is so funny, he asked me - if I'd go to a dance, they were late dances. So - I said - to my mother - that was before he
 
was going away, I - I - I I didn't go regular with him, I just used to meet him and that was all, not in - I whether he was too shy or frightened I don't know what. However - she says, who are you going with? I says, a soldier. Oh who is he? And I told he
r
, I says, well that's all I know. Oh. She remembered, she went - and got me a lovely - jap silk blouse, in a drapers, mind now in the drapers it used to be in Dumfries, it was the place you could anything from a needle to an anchor nearly. And - I think I
 
had a black pleated skirt and this white jap silk blouse with big - diamond buttons on it. Just a - it was a late - what they call a late dance, was in the drill hall which is Lorburn Hall now, and of course I met a girl I knew and she was going. So I sai
d
, well I'll see you there. So - he came for me, the bell rung, we lived in Queensbury Street then, and - I said, that'll be him. So - came upstairs, and - I introduced him to my mother. So when we were going down the stairs I nearly fell down the stair - 
well I says - my mother says, now - see you bring her back the way you took her. Nearly died.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 What did he say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
I never spoke. Neither did he. So we - went at the dance and I danced with a few }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 fellows}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  that's knew and that, and had the last - he says, come on I'm taking you home, he said, and I'll }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 had}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
 you over to your mother. So he did, rung the bell. And - it was four years - I was married 1917 and I think I'd only been his company - kind at that time about - a month, al with weekends and days, him coming - on leave. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 He would write plenty of letters though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes, he was in France then. Used to come home from France, and then - he came home, he was going to - he was going to - be an instructor you see and had to go to different sch
ools, gunnery schools in England, and - he used to come home a bit oftener then and then we got married. He was at tunbury when we got married, he came from Tunbury, but - it was difficult to get away 'cos the best man couldn't come, they just let him awa
y. I got a wire to say he was coming on the Saturday and I didn't know whether we was getting married or not, because he couldn't arrange anything. Couldn't arrange a date.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you get engaged?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh yes, I got engaged, he was in Hyde, he sent me th
e ring up from Hyde. And - he came to Tunbury, to the school of gunnery of Tunbury, and - we had said like - he said, get married in perhaps about February sometime, he - he couldn't - couldn't say a date. And - just didn't know. So I got to this wire to 
s
ay he was coming, and - I had to wire back to say well was he - what - was - was he - were we being married or what was happening you see. He said yes. So he came on the Saturday night. But the best - he was bringing another - airman with him you see, and
 - he wouldn't - they would only let him away because there was a big push on at the time you know. Over in France, that was in the first world - 1917, and - we'd to go and hunt a best man. Which I got.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Would you find one of your relations or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Yes, I found - no, I knew - I knew this - where he belonged, he was at Arrol Jonsons at the time and I knew him and - I knew his wife too, he's married, but we went - they'd no children or anything, so he was my best man, and - then they
'd to go to the - to the minister - go to the - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 sheriff}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
 - and your name - instead of being called -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you do all this yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
He done it. Ah, he done - that - that - oh that - on the Monday. On the Monday. Sunday night we looked for the 
best - for the best man and - I knew my chum was going to be my braidesmaid you see, best - of course we were married in - in the - in the manse, not in the church, and - you couldn't have - a wedding dress, you just had to have a - a new - suit which I d
i
d have, I had it made and that and - we went to the - who was the Sherrif then? The Municipal Chanbers. The minister, well it was - Jamieson, the Reverend Jamieson, went with - the - Sherrif, got all the - things made out. I was married six o'clock at nig
h
t. And my mother - and all her friends - got together, yes, on a Monday, got together - and we had a wedding, we had their - about thirty people at the - in the house, and got - she got the loan of - trestles from Oatens. Mm. Boiled tongues and - goodness
 knows what all, bot -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 You would have a hectic weekend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 And we had a grand - a grand wedding. Feast and all. And - I }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 invited}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  whoever - just to go and ask them to come you see. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was it the sort of habit then, being difficult times like t
hat, there was a wedding sort of unexpectedly everybody joined in and took something with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No - well maybe they - but my mother - you know - everybody belongs to me brought something you know, and made cakes and made - different things and she got stuff from Oatens too - you know, it's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 marvellous}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  - how they can do these things. Or how - how they did them. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Did you have a wedding cake?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
No. I had a wedding cake but no icing, there was no icing on them, it was just a plain - fruit cake. No icing - icing sugar.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was that because of rationing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 
Oh yes. It stopped all that you see, stopped all that. No icing. And when my daughter got married she was nearly the same, she got the last one out of Dunbar the bakers on the High Stree
t, a three tier one, it was pink, and after that there was no cakes with icing on. That was - another - 1940. So - but mine was 1917. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 
And - what was I going to say - oh - the taxi came, six o'clock, and they used to say about bad luck seeing your future hu
sband in the house, and he had to sleep in that house that night so - see him all day, night and all, and - we went to the Manse, and - best man, best maid, they're all waiting at home for us coming back you see, getting the feast ready. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 And - the minister
 says, have you got the marriage lines? He says, yes, took them out of his pocket. He says, have you got not the blue ones? No, he says, that's all the man had got. It was a certificate. Oh, he says, did you not get the other ones? Well then - he says - w
h
at have you got at the door? Taxi. Come on son, I'll see you married if it's twelve o'clock, we'll have to go and get the Registrar up - to fill in the marriage lines, you've got a certificate but it hasn't got the marriage lines. Away they went. I think 
I
 was married, I don't know how often. The best man reading it out of the book - in the Manse. He got the Bible and he read the marriage service to me, and - and the - the best maid of course she was there too, I thought they were never coming back. The mu
n
icipal chambers was closed, and - they'd to go away to Victoria Terrace and - get the Registrar out of his bed nearly I think, I think he'd been home for the night, and - he came to the municipal chambers and they got all the things out you know, filled a
l
l these in, my mother's name and your father's name, how know, what's the - the long certificate, and they came back. And you - my mother taught we had went away, she - oh they were all up to hunt me, somebody came round and no taxi there, of course we we
re in the Manse at the time but the taxi had gone. And mother was off the high door, what she'd do to me for doing a thing like that. However we landed home.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 When did you finally get married then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Then. Oh - oh - about eight o'clock. They were a
bout two hours away. I couldn't tell them. However - after we explained it all - so the minister says I'll - I'll see you married boy, he says, if it's twelve o'clock tonight. It was like a picture you know. And - your names weren't called in the church t
he same as they are now. My name - was put on - Greyfriars Parish - door - on the door, and on St Michaels, and hung there for a fortnight our two - two names on the door for everybody to read. But that was the banns.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Was that done before or after?
