en, but - just - he got me - rooms and - and - he slept there, at that place I stayed but he got his food down at the - in the camp and I had my food with the people that I stayed with. Then I used to go and meet him coming back home at night. Oh we were 
q
uite - we were innocent those days, not like now. Learnt a lot since then. Oh - but he was - a fine fellow he was. Ah. And I - I was twenty-five years away - with him in different places. Oh I lived a - a proper - pioneers - ay, in - in - rooms and in fur
nished houses and then - when I was at East Church in Kent we got a house, furnished it, I was eight years there. Then - had to be put in store and go somewhere else. I ended up - I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12191358\charrsid8598525 ended}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525  up in Wales during this war, two wars I was in. My husband was - stil
l a - gunnery and bombing instructor, and - came home here to Dumfries in 1946.
