\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16721817 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 I know you said your mother used to help people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11304503 JH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14574712\charrsid8598525 Oh my
 mother used to - oh - my mother used to, of course we were just - we just had to - depend on our mother and father looking after us. But we didn't have much money ourself, but - it never used to bother us. Never used to bother me as long as I had - three
p
ence or sixpence in my pocket. Go a long way that did. And when I was at the school if you had a penny that went long way, of course what you got for a penny. You - you'd spend a ha'penny, get maybe four aniseed balls and - a strip of licorice, and someth
i
ng else for a - for a halfpenny. And every year my - my granny always used to give us a shilling, and you thought you were Carnegie, you changed it into coppers and you were rattling it about in your pocket, you thought you were Carnegie, with twelve penc
e, coppers. Because you could get such a lot for one penny.
